1
00:00:01,810 --> 00:00:06,480
Miracles

2
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:14,580
Who am I? And how, I wonder, will this story
end?

3
00:00:14,580 --> 00:00:19,869
The sun has come up and I am sitting by a
window that is foggy with the breath of a

4
00:00:19,869 --> 00:00:29,910
life gone by. I’m a sight this morning:
two shirts, heavy pants, a scarf wrapped twice

5
00:00:29,910 --> 00:00:38,370
around my neck and tucked into a thick sweater
knitted by my daughter thirty birthdays ago.

6
00:00:38,370 --> 00:00:44,890
The thermostat in my room is set as high as
it will go, and a smaller space heater sits

7
00:00:44,890 --> 00:00:53,649
directly behind me. It clicks and groans and
spews hot air like a fairy-tale dragon, and

8
00:00:53,649 --> 00:01:01,390
still my body shivers with a cold that will
never go away, a cold that has been eighty

9
00:01:01,390 --> 00:01:09,280
years in the making. Eighty years, I think
sometimes, and despite my own acceptance of

10
00:01:09,280 --> 00:01:18,510
my age, it still amazes me that I haven’t
been warm since George Bush was president.

11
00:01:18,510 --> 00:01:23,750
I wonder if this is how it is for everyone
my age.

12
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:31,320
My life? It isn’t easy to explain. It has
not been the rip-roaring spectacular I fancied

13
00:01:31,320 --> 00:01:39,530
it would be, but neither have I burrowed around
with the gophers. I suppose it has most resembled

14
00:01:39,530 --> 00:01:47,869
a blue-chip stock: fairly stable, more ups
than downs, and gradually trending upward

15
00:01:47,869 --> 00:01:55,960
over time. A good buy, a lucky buy, and I’ve
learned that not everyone can say this about

16
00:01:55,960 --> 00:02:06,070
his life. But do not be misled. I am nothing
special; of this I am sure. I am a common

17
00:02:06,070 --> 00:02:14,290
man with common thoughts, and I’ve led a
common life. There are no monuments dedicated

18
00:02:14,290 --> 00:02:23,830
to me and my name will soon be forgotten,
but I’ve loved another with all my heart

19
00:02:23,830 --> 00:02:31,459
and soul, and to me, this has always been
enough.

20
00:02:31,459 --> 00:02:39,080
The romantics would call this a love story,
the cynics would call it a tragedy. In my

21
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:46,580
mind it’s a little bit of both, and no matter
how you choose to view it in the end, it does

22
00:02:46,580 --> 00:02:53,330
not change the fact that it involves a great
deal of my life and the path I’ve chosen

23
00:02:53,330 --> 00:03:02,170
to follow. I have no complaints about my path
and the places it has taken me; enough complaints

24
00:03:02,170 --> 00:03:07,430
to fill a circus tent about other things,
maybe, but the path I’ve chosen has always

25
00:03:07,430 --> 00:03:15,069
been the right one, and I wouldn’t have
had it any other way.

26
00:03:15,069 --> 00:03:23,650
Time, unfortunately, doesn’t make it easy
to stay on course. The path is straight as

27
00:03:23,650 --> 00:03:31,160
ever, but now it is strewn with the rocks
and gravel that accumulate over a lifetime.

28
00:03:31,160 --> 00:03:38,151
Until three years ago it would have been easy
to ignore, but it’s impossible now. There

29
00:03:38,151 --> 00:03:46,080
is a sickness rolling through my body; I’m
neither strong nor healthy, and my days are

30
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:55,569
spent like an old party balloon: listless,
spongy, and growing softer over time.

31
00:03:55,569 --> 00:04:04,750
I cough, and through squinted eyes I check
my watch. I realize it is time to go. I stand

32
00:04:04,750 --> 00:04:11,780
from my seat by the window and shuffle across
the room, stopping at the desk to pick up

33
00:04:11,780 --> 00:04:19,780
the notebook I have read a hundred times.
I do not glance through it. Instead I slip

34
00:04:19,780 --> 00:04:27,350
it beneath my arm and continue on my way to
the place I must go.

35
00:04:27,350 --> 00:04:35,530
I walk on tiled floors, white in color and
speckled with gray. Like my hair and the hair

36
00:04:35,530 --> 00:04:41,319
of most people here, though I’m the only
one in the hallway this morning. They are

37
00:04:41,319 --> 00:04:48,631
in their rooms, alone except for television,
but they, like me, are used to it. A person

38
00:04:48,631 --> 00:04:54,320
can get used to anything, if given enough
time.

39
00:04:54,320 --> 00:05:01,310
I hear the muffled sounds of crying in the
distance and know exactly who is making those

40
00:05:01,310 --> 00:05:08,820
sounds. Then the nurses see me and we smile
at each other and exchange greetings. They

41
00:05:08,820 --> 00:05:15,470
are my friends and we talk often, but I am
sure they wonder about me and the things that

42
00:05:15,470 --> 00:05:22,699
I go through every day. I listen as they begin
to whisper among themselves as I pass. “There

43
00:05:22,699 --> 00:05:30,120
he goes again,” I hear, “I hope it turns
out well.” But they say nothing directly

44
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:36,760
to me about it. I’m sure they think it would
hurt me to talk about it so early in the morning,

45
00:05:36,760 --> 00:05:43,670
and knowing myself as I do, I think they’re
probably right.

46
00:05:43,670 --> 00:05:49,970
A minute later, I reach the room. The door
has been propped open for me, as it usually

47
00:05:49,970 --> 00:05:56,450
is. There are two others in the room, and
they too smile at me as I enter. “Good morning,”

48
00:05:56,450 --> 00:06:03,330
they say with cheery voices, and I take a
moment to ask about the kids and the schools

49
00:06:03,330 --> 00:06:10,889
and upcoming vacations. We talk above the
crying for a minute or so. They do not seem

50
00:06:10,889 --> 00:06:18,650
to notice; they have become numb to it, but
then again, so have I.

51
00:06:18,650 --> 00:06:24,599
Afterward I sit in the chair that has come
to be shaped like me. They are finishing up

52
00:06:24,599 --> 00:06:32,440
now; her clothes are on, but still she is
crying. It will become quieter after they

53
00:06:32,440 --> 00:06:40,479
leave, I know. The excitement of the morning
always upsets her, and today is no exception.

54
00:06:40,479 --> 00:06:47,390
Finally the shade is opened and the nurses
walk out. Both of them touch me and smile

55
00:06:47,390 --> 00:06:53,130
as they walk by. I wonder what this means.

56
00:06:53,130 --> 00:07:01,250
I sit for just a second and stare at her,
but she doesn’t return the look. I understand,

57
00:07:01,250 --> 00:07:11,000
for she doesn’t know who I am. I’m a stranger
to her. Then, turning away, I bow my head

58
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:19,319
and pray silently for the strength I know
I will need. I have always been a firm believer

59
00:07:19,319 --> 00:07:25,450
in God and the power of prayer, though to
be honest, my faith has made for a list of

60
00:07:25,450 --> 00:07:30,960
questions I definitely want answered after
I’m gone.

61
00:07:30,960 --> 00:07:40,139
Ready now. On go the glasses, out of my pocket
comes a magnifier. I put it on the table for

62
00:07:40,139 --> 00:07:46,750
a moment while I open the notebook. It takes
two licks on my gnarled finger to get the

63
00:07:46,750 --> 00:07:54,849
well-worn cover open to the first page. Then
I put the magnifier in place.

64
00:07:54,849 --> 00:08:01,430
There is always a moment right before I begin
to read the story when my mind churns, and

65
00:08:01,430 --> 00:08:08,990
I wonder, Will it happen today? I don’t
know, for I never know beforehand, and deep

66
00:08:08,990 --> 00:08:16,949
down it really doesn’t matter. It’s the
possibility that keeps me going, not the guarantee,

67
00:08:16,949 --> 00:08:24,370
a sort of wager on my part. And though you
may call me a dreamer or fool or any other

68
00:08:24,370 --> 00:08:30,280
thing, I believe that anything is possible.

69
00:08:30,280 --> 00:08:38,479
I realize the odds, and science, are against
me. But science is not the total answer; this

70
00:08:38,479 --> 00:08:46,589
I know, this I have learned in my lifetime.
And that leaves me with the belief that miracles,

71
00:08:46,589 --> 00:08:54,380
no matter how inexplicable or unbelievable,
are real and can occur without regard to the

72
00:08:54,380 --> 00:09:04,290
natural order of things. So once again, just
as I do every day, I begin to read the notebook

73
00:09:04,290 --> 00:09:10,010
aloud, so that she can hear it, in the hope
that the miracle that has come to dominate

74
00:09:10,010 --> 00:09:15,010
my life will once again prevail.

75
00:09:15,010 --> 00:09:23,410
And maybe, just maybe, it will.

76
00:09:23,410 --> 00:09:27,079
Ghosts

77
00:09:27,079 --> 00:09:39,149
It was early October 1946, and Noah Calhoun
watched the fading sun sink lower from the

78
00:09:39,149 --> 00:09:48,890
wraparound porch of his plantation-style home.
He liked to sit here in the evenings, especially

79
00:09:48,890 --> 00:09:56,030
after working hard all day, and let his thoughts
wander without conscious direction. It was

80
00:09:56,030 --> 00:10:02,709
how he relaxed, a routine he’d learned from
his father.

81
00:10:02,709 --> 00:10:09,480
He especially liked to look at the trees and
their reflections in the river. North Carolina

82
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:20,360
trees are beautiful in deep autumn: greens,
yellows, reds, oranges, every shade in between.

83
00:10:20,360 --> 00:10:30,610
Their dazzling colors glow with the sun, and
for the hundredth time, Noah Calhoun wondered

84
00:10:30,610 --> 00:10:37,380
if the original owners of the house had spent
their evenings thinking the same things.

85
00:10:37,380 --> 00:10:48,860
The house was built in 1772, making it one
of the oldest, as well as largest, homes in

86
00:10:48,860 --> 00:10:54,700
New Bern. Originally it was the main house
on a working plantation, and he had bought

87
00:10:54,700 --> 00:11:00,490
it right after the war ended and had spent
the last eleven months and a small fortune

88
00:11:00,490 --> 00:11:06,279
repairing it. The reporter from the Raleigh
paper had done an article on it a few weeks

89
00:11:06,279 --> 00:11:14,529
ago and said it was one of the finest restorations
he’d ever seen. At least the house was.

90
00:11:14,529 --> 00:11:20,110
The remaining property was another story,
and that was where he’d spent most of the

91
00:11:20,110 --> 00:11:22,339
day.

92
00:11:22,339 --> 00:11:29,420
The home sat on twelve acres adjacent to Brices
Creek, and he’d worked on the wooden fence

93
00:11:29,420 --> 00:11:36,190
that lined the other three sides of the property,
checking for dry rot or termites, replacing

94
00:11:36,190 --> 00:11:43,390
posts when he had to. He still had more work
to do on it, especially on the west side,

95
00:11:43,390 --> 00:11:49,240
and as he’d put the tools away earlier he’d
made a mental note to call and have some more

96
00:11:49,240 --> 00:11:57,230
lumber delivered. He’d gone into the house,
drunk a glass of sweet tea, then showered.

97
00:11:57,230 --> 00:12:05,820
He always showered at the end of the day,
the water washing away both dirt and fatigue.

98
00:12:05,820 --> 00:12:15,820
Afterward he’d combed his hair back, put
on some faded jeans and a long-sleeved blue

99
00:12:15,820 --> 00:12:24,250
shirt, poured himself another glass of sweet
tea, and gone to the porch, where he now sat,

100
00:12:24,250 --> 00:12:27,709
where he sat every day at this time.

101
00:12:27,709 --> 00:12:32,780
He stretched his arms above his head, then
out to the sides, rolling his shoulders as

102
00:12:32,780 --> 00:12:39,380
he completed the routine. He felt good and
clean now, fresh. His muscles were tired and

103
00:12:39,380 --> 00:12:44,000
he knew he’d be a little sore tomorrow,
but he was pleased that he had accomplished

104
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:47,250
most of what he had wanted to do.

105
00:12:47,250 --> 00:12:52,019
Noah reached for his guitar, remembering his
father as he did so, thinking how much he

106
00:12:52,019 --> 00:12:59,160
missed him. He strummed once, adjusted the
tension on two strings, then strummed again.

107
00:12:59,160 --> 00:13:07,329
This time it sounded about right, and he began
to play. Soft music, quiet music. He hummed

108
00:13:07,329 --> 00:13:13,040
for a little while at first, then began to
sing as night came down around him. He played

109
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:19,530
and sang until the sun was gone and the sky
was black.

110
00:13:19,530 --> 00:13:23,440
It was a little after seven when he quit,
and he settled back into his chair and began

111
00:13:23,440 --> 00:13:29,950
to rock. By habit, he looked upward and saw
Orion and the Big Dipper, Gemini and the Pole

112
00:13:29,950 --> 00:13:32,900
Star, twinkling in the autumn sky.

113
00:13:32,900 --> 00:13:38,160
He started to run the numbers in his head,
then stopped. He knew he’d spent almost

114
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:43,600
his entire savings on the house and would
have to find a job again soon, but he pushed

115
00:13:43,600 --> 00:13:48,339
the thought away and decided to enjoy the
remaining months of restoration without worrying

116
00:13:48,339 --> 00:13:55,130
about it. It would work out for him, he knew;
it always did. Besides, thinking about money

117
00:13:55,130 --> 00:14:01,120
usually bored him. Early on, he’d learned
to enjoy simple things, things that couldn’t

118
00:14:01,120 --> 00:14:06,959
be bought, and he had a hard time understanding
people who felt otherwise. It was another

119
00:14:06,959 --> 00:14:09,440
trait he got from his father.

120
00:14:09,440 --> 00:14:16,250
Clem, his hound dog, came up to him then and
nuzzled his hand before lying down at his

121
00:14:16,250 --> 00:14:21,260
feet. “Hey, girl, how’re you doing?”
he asked as he patted her head, and she whined

122
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:27,860
softly, her soft round eyes peering upward.
A car accident had taken her leg, but she

123
00:14:27,860 --> 00:14:33,250
still moved well enough and kept him company
on quiet nights like these.

124
00:14:33,250 --> 00:14:39,720
He was thirty-one now, not too old, but old
enough to be lonely. He hadn’t dated since

125
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:45,750
he’d been back here, hadn’t met anyone
who remotely interested him. It was his own

126
00:14:45,750 --> 00:14:51,560
fault, he knew. There was something that kept
a distance between him and any woman who started

127
00:14:51,560 --> 00:14:58,480
to get close, something he wasn’t sure he
could change even if he tried. And sometimes

128
00:14:58,480 --> 00:15:06,970
in the moments right before sleep came, he
wondered if he was destined to be alone forever.

129
00:15:06,970 --> 00:15:13,390
The evening passed, staying warm, nice. Noah
listened to the crickets and the rustling

130
00:15:13,390 --> 00:15:18,259
leaves, thinking that the sound of nature
was more real and aroused more emotion than

131
00:15:18,259 --> 00:15:25,340
things like cars and planes. Natural things
gave back more than they took, and their sounds

132
00:15:25,340 --> 00:15:31,240
always brought him back to the way man was
supposed to be. There were times during the

133
00:15:31,240 --> 00:15:36,760
war, especially after a major engagement,
when he had often thought about these simple

134
00:15:36,760 --> 00:15:42,560
sounds. “It’ll keep you from going crazy,”
his father had told him the day he’d shipped

135
00:15:42,560 --> 00:15:48,459
out. “It’s God’s music and it’ll take
you home.”

136
00:15:48,459 --> 00:15:53,819
He finished his tea, went inside, found a
book, then turned on the porch light on his

137
00:15:53,819 --> 00:15:59,460
way back out. After sitting down again, he
looked at the book. It was old, the cover

138
00:15:59,460 --> 00:16:06,030
was torn, and the pages were stained with
mud and water. It was Leaves of Grass by Walt

139
00:16:06,030 --> 00:16:12,009
Whitman, and he had carried it with him throughout
the war. It had even taken a bullet for him

140
00:16:12,009 --> 00:16:13,579
once.

141
00:16:13,579 --> 00:16:19,540
He rubbed the cover, dusting it off just a
little. Then he let the book open randomly

142
00:16:19,540 --> 00:16:22,750
and read the words in front of him:

143
00:16:22,750 --> 00:16:28,940
This is thy hour O Soul, thy free flight into
the wordless,

144
00:16:28,940 --> 00:16:35,920
Away from books, away from art, the day erased,
the lesson done,

145
00:16:35,920 --> 00:16:45,180
Thee fully forth emerging, silent, gazing,
pondering the themes thou lovest best,

146
00:16:45,180 --> 00:16:56,639
Night, sleep, death and the stars.
He smiled to himself. For some reason Whitman

147
00:16:56,639 --> 00:17:01,779
always reminded him of New Bern, and he was
glad he’d come back. Though he’d been

148
00:17:01,779 --> 00:17:06,929
away for fourteen years, this was home and
he knew a lot of people here, most of them

149
00:17:06,929 --> 00:17:13,670
from his youth. It wasn’t surprising. Like
so many southern towns, the people who lived

150
00:17:13,670 --> 00:17:20,000
here never changed, they just grew a bit older.

151
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:26,900
His best friend these days was Gus, a seventy-year-old
black man who lived down the road. They had

152
00:17:26,900 --> 00:17:31,610
met a couple of weeks after Noah bought the
house, when Gus had shown up with some homemade

153
00:17:31,610 --> 00:17:36,559
liquor and Brunswick stew, and the two had
spent their first evening together getting

154
00:17:36,559 --> 00:17:39,270
drunk and telling stories.

155
00:17:39,270 --> 00:17:46,010
Now Gus would show up a couple of nights a
week, usually around eight. With four kids

156
00:17:46,010 --> 00:17:51,510
and eleven grandchildren in the house, he
needed to get out of the house now and then,

157
00:17:51,510 --> 00:17:56,580
and Noah couldn’t blame him. Usually Gus
would bring his harmonica, and after talking

158
00:17:56,580 --> 00:18:02,539
for a little while, they’d play a few songs
together. Sometimes they played for hours.

159
00:18:02,539 --> 00:18:08,909
He’d come to regard Gus as family. There
really wasn’t anyone else, at least not

160
00:18:08,909 --> 00:18:15,390
since his father died last year. He was an
only child; his mother had died of influenza

161
00:18:15,390 --> 00:18:21,260
when he was two, and though he had wanted
to at one time, he had never married.

162
00:18:21,260 --> 00:18:29,990
But he had been in love once, that he knew.
Once and only once, and a long time ago. And

163
00:18:29,990 --> 00:18:41,830
it had changed him forever. Perfect love did
that to a person, and this had been perfect.

164
00:18:41,830 --> 00:18:47,920
Coastal clouds slowly began to roll across
the evening sky, turning silver with the reflection

165
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:54,179
of the moon. As they thickened, he leaned
his head back and rested it against the rocking

166
00:18:54,179 --> 00:19:00,150
chair. His legs moved automatically, keeping
a steady rhythm, and as he did most evenings,

167
00:19:00,150 --> 00:19:07,170
he felt his mind drifting back to a warm evening
like this fourteen years ago.

168
00:19:07,170 --> 00:19:14,991
It was just after graduation 1932, the opening
night of the Neuse River Festival. The town

169
00:19:14,991 --> 00:19:22,091
was out in full, enjoying barbecue and games
of chance. It was humid that night—for some

170
00:19:22,091 --> 00:19:28,850
reason he remembered that clearly. He arrived
alone, and as he strolled through the crowd,

171
00:19:28,850 --> 00:19:33,780
looking for friends, he saw Fin and Sarah,
two people he’d grown up with, talking to

172
00:19:33,780 --> 00:19:39,789
a girl he’d never seen before. She was pretty,
he remembered thinking, and when he finally

173
00:19:39,789 --> 00:19:47,480
joined them, she looked his way with a pair
of hazy eyes that kept on coming. “Hi,”

174
00:19:47,480 --> 00:19:54,429
she’d said simply as she offered her hand,
“Finley’s told me a lot about you.”

175
00:19:54,429 --> 00:19:59,950
An ordinary beginning, something that would
have been forgotten had it been anyone but

176
00:19:59,950 --> 00:20:08,320
her. But as he shook her hand and met those
striking emerald eyes, he knew before he’d

177
00:20:08,320 --> 00:20:13,110
taken his next breath that she was the one
he could spend the rest of his life looking

178
00:20:13,110 --> 00:20:22,740
for but never find again. She seemed that
good, that perfect, while a summer wind blew

179
00:20:22,740 --> 00:20:25,580
through the trees.

180
00:20:25,580 --> 00:20:31,720
From there, it went like a tornado wind. Fin
told him she was spending the summer in New

181
00:20:31,720 --> 00:20:36,440
Bern with her family because her father worked
for R. J. Reynolds, and though he only nodded,

182
00:20:36,440 --> 00:20:42,820
the way she was looking at him made his silence
seem okay. Fin laughed then, because he knew

183
00:20:42,820 --> 00:20:48,320
what was happening, and Sarah suggested they
get some cherry Cokes, and the four of them

184
00:20:48,320 --> 00:20:54,409
stayed at the festival until the crowds were
thin and everything closed up for the night.

185
00:20:54,409 --> 00:21:01,611
They met the following day, and the day after
that, and they soon became inseparable. Every

186
00:21:01,611 --> 00:21:07,470
morning but Sunday when he had to go to church,
he would finish his chores as quickly as possible,

187
00:21:07,470 --> 00:21:12,911
then make a straight line to Fort Totten Park,
where she’d be waiting for him. Because

188
00:21:12,911 --> 00:21:17,850
she was a newcomer and hadn’t spent time
in a small town before, they spent their days

189
00:21:17,850 --> 00:21:23,440
doing things that were completely new to her.
He taught her how to bait a line and fish

190
00:21:23,440 --> 00:21:28,159
the shallows for largemouth bass and took
her exploring through the backwoods of the

191
00:21:28,159 --> 00:21:35,200
Croatan Forest. They rode in canoes and watched
