00:40:44,220 --> 00:40:50,380
them. An occasional person found him arrogant;
most simply figured he had grown up a bit

384
00:40:50,380 --> 00:40:56,670
faster than everyone else. He had a few girlfriends
in school, but none had ever made an impression

385
00:40:56,670 --> 00:41:01,930
on him. Except for one. And she came after
graduation.

386
00:41:01,930 --> 00:41:06,670
Allie. His Allie.

387
00:41:06,670 --> 00:41:11,701
He remembered talking to Fin about Allie after
they’d left the festival that first night,

388
00:41:11,701 --> 00:41:18,180
and Fin had laughed. Then he’d made two
predictions: first, that they would fall in

389
00:41:18,180 --> 00:41:24,240
love, and second, that it wouldn’t work
out.

390
00:41:24,240 --> 00:41:28,910
There was a slight tug at his line and Noah
hoped for a largemouth bass, but the tugging

391
00:41:28,910 --> 00:41:36,329
eventually stopped, and after reeling his
line in and checking the bait, he cast again.

392
00:41:36,329 --> 00:41:43,099
Fin ended up being right on both counts. Most
of the summer, she had to make excuses to

393
00:41:43,099 --> 00:41:48,230
her parents whenever they wanted to see each
other. It wasn’t that they didn’t like

394
00:41:48,230 --> 00:41:53,850
him—it was that he was from a different
class, too poor, and they would never approve

395
00:41:53,850 --> 00:42:00,300
if their daughter became serious with someone
like him. “I don’t care what my parents

396
00:42:00,300 --> 00:42:07,160
think, I love you and always will,” she
would say. “We’ll find a way to be together.”

397
00:42:07,160 --> 00:42:13,680
But in the end they couldn’t. By early September
the tobacco had been harvested and she had

398
00:42:13,680 --> 00:42:20,400
no choice but to return with her family to
Winston-Salem. “Only the summer is over,

399
00:42:20,400 --> 00:42:27,740
Allie, not us,” he’d said the morning
she left. “We’ll never be over.” But

400
00:42:27,740 --> 00:42:35,970
they were. For a reason he didn’t fully
understand, the letters he wrote went unanswered.

401
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:44,180
Eventually he decided to leave New Bern to
help get her off his mind, but also because

402
00:42:44,180 --> 00:42:49,940
the Depression made earning a living in New
Bern almost impossible. He went first to Norfolk

403
00:42:49,940 --> 00:42:55,590
and worked at a shipyard for six months before
he was laid off, then moved to New Jersey

404
00:42:55,590 --> 00:42:59,500
because he’d heard the economy wasn’t
so bad there.

405
00:42:59,500 --> 00:43:05,339
He eventually found a job in a scrap yard,
separating scrap metal from everything else.

406
00:43:05,339 --> 00:43:11,570
The owner, a Jewish man named Morris Goldman,
was intent on collecting as much scrap metal

407
00:43:11,570 --> 00:43:17,120
as he could, convinced that a war was going
to start in Europe and that America would

408
00:43:17,120 --> 00:43:22,950
be dragged in again. Noah, though, didn’t
care about the reason. He was just happy to

409
00:43:22,950 --> 00:43:24,470
have a job.

410
00:43:24,470 --> 00:43:30,540
His years in the lumberyard had toughened
him to this type of labor, and he worked hard.

411
00:43:30,540 --> 00:43:34,510
Not only did it help him keep his mind off
Allie during the day, but it was something

412
00:43:34,510 --> 00:43:40,210
he felt he had to do. His daddy had always
said: “Give a day’s work for a day’s

413
00:43:40,210 --> 00:43:47,430
pay. Anything less is stealing.” That attitude
pleased his boss. “It’s a shame you aren’t

414
00:43:47,430 --> 00:43:52,960
Jewish,” Goldman would say, “you’re
such a fine boy in so many other ways.”

415
00:43:52,960 --> 00:43:57,349
It was the best compliment Goldman could give.

416
00:43:57,349 --> 00:44:03,370
He continued to think about Allie, especially
at night. He wrote her once a month but never

417
00:44:03,370 --> 00:44:10,930
received a reply. Eventually he wrote a final
letter and forced himself to accept the fact

418
00:44:10,930 --> 00:44:16,740
that the summer they’d spent with one another
was the only thing they’d ever share.

419
00:44:16,740 --> 00:44:22,860
Still, though, she stayed with him. Three
years after the last letter, he went to Winston-Salem

420
00:44:22,860 --> 00:44:27,849
in the hope of finding her. He went to her
house, discovered that she had moved, and

421
00:44:27,849 --> 00:44:33,500
after talking to some neighbors, finally called
RJR. The girl who answered the phone was new

422
00:44:33,500 --> 00:44:38,750
and didn’t recognize the name, but she poked
around the personnel files for him. She found

423
00:44:38,750 --> 00:44:44,619
out that Allie’s father had left the company
and that no forwarding address was listed.

424
00:44:44,619 --> 00:44:49,760
That trip was the first and last time he ever
looked for her.

425
00:44:49,760 --> 00:44:54,900
For the next eight years, he worked for Goldman.
At first he was one of twelve employees, but

426
00:44:54,900 --> 00:45:00,619
as the years dragged on, the company grew,
and he was promoted. By 1940 he had mastered

427
00:45:00,619 --> 00:45:06,160
the business and was running the entire operation,
brokering the deals and managing a staff of

428
00:45:06,160 --> 00:45:11,140
thirty. The yard had become the largest scrap
metal dealer on the East Coast.

429
00:45:11,140 --> 00:45:17,650
During that time, he dated a few different
women. He became serious with one, a waitress

430
00:45:17,650 --> 00:45:22,950
from the local diner with deep blue eyes and
silky black hair. Although they dated for

431
00:45:22,950 --> 00:45:28,480
two years and had many good times together,
he never came to feel the same way about her

432
00:45:28,480 --> 00:45:30,920
as he did about Allie.

433
00:45:30,920 --> 00:45:36,170
But neither did he forget her. She was a few
years older than he was, and it was she who

434
00:45:36,170 --> 00:45:41,980
taught him the ways to please a woman, the
places to touch and kiss, where to linger,

435
00:45:41,980 --> 00:45:47,960
the things to whisper. They would sometimes
spend an entire day in bed, holding each other

436
00:45:47,960 --> 00:45:52,600
and making the kind of love that fully satisfied
both of them.

437
00:45:52,600 --> 00:45:56,770
She had known they wouldn’t be together
forever. Toward the end of their relationship

438
00:45:56,770 --> 00:46:01,780
she’d told him once, “I wish I could give
you what you’re looking for, but I don’t

439
00:46:01,780 --> 00:46:07,130
know what it is. There’s a part of you that
you keep closed off from everyone, including

440
00:46:07,130 --> 00:46:15,630
me. It’s as if I’m not the one you’re
really with. Your mind is on someone else.”

441
00:46:15,630 --> 00:46:21,819
He tried to deny it, but she didn’t believe
him. “I’m a woman—I know these things.

442
00:46:21,819 --> 00:46:27,680
When you look at me sometimes, I know you’re
seeing someone else. It’s like you keep

443
00:46:27,680 --> 00:46:35,430
waiting for her to pop out of thin air to
take you away from all this. . . .” A month

444
00:46:35,430 --> 00:46:40,960
later she visited him at work and told him
she’d met someone else. He understood. They

445
00:46:40,960 --> 00:46:45,869
parted as friends, and the following year
he received a postcard from her saying she

446
00:46:45,869 --> 00:46:50,510
was married. He hadn’t heard from her since.

447
00:46:50,510 --> 00:46:55,119
While he was in New Jersey, he would visit
his father once a year around Christmas. They’d

448
00:46:55,119 --> 00:46:59,890
spend some time fishing and talking, and once
in a while they’d take a trip to the coast

449
00:46:59,890 --> 00:47:04,150
to go camping on the Outer Banks near Ocracoke.

450
00:47:04,150 --> 00:47:12,290
In December 1941, when he was twenty-six,
the war began, just as Goldman had predicted.

451
00:47:12,290 --> 00:47:17,180
Noah walked into his office the following
month and informed Goldman of his intent to

452
00:47:17,180 --> 00:47:23,990
enlist, then returned to New Bern to say good-bye
to his father. Five weeks later he found himself

453
00:47:23,990 --> 00:47:29,830
in boot camp. While there, he received a letter
from Goldman thanking him for his work, together

454
00:47:29,830 --> 00:47:35,369
with a copy of a certificate entitling him
to a small percentage of the scrap yard if

455
00:47:35,369 --> 00:47:40,610
it ever sold. “I couldn’t have done it
without you,” the letter said. “You’re

456
00:47:40,610 --> 00:47:46,920
the finest young man who ever worked for me,
even if you aren’t Jewish.”

457
00:47:46,920 --> 00:47:52,470
He spent his next three years with Patton’s
Third Army, tramping through deserts in North

458
00:47:52,470 --> 00:47:58,410
Africa and forests in Europe with thirty pounds
on his back, his infantry unit never far from

459
00:47:58,410 --> 00:48:05,569
action. He watched his friends die around
him; watched as some of them were buried thousands

460
00:48:05,569 --> 00:48:11,140
of miles from home. Once, while hiding in
a foxhole near the Rhine, he imagined he saw

461
00:48:11,140 --> 00:48:13,860
Allie watching over him.

462
00:48:13,860 --> 00:48:19,100
He remembered the war ending in Europe, then
a few months later in Japan. Just before he

463
00:48:19,100 --> 00:48:24,050
was discharged, he received a letter from
a lawyer in New Jersey representing Morris

464
00:48:24,050 --> 00:48:29,650
Goldman. Upon meeting the lawyer, he found
out that Goldman had died a year earlier and

465
00:48:29,650 --> 00:48:35,359
his estate liquidated. The business had been
sold, and Noah was given a check for almost

466
00:48:35,359 --> 00:48:41,960
seventy thousand dollars. For some reason
he was oddly unexcited about it.

467
00:48:41,960 --> 00:48:46,550
The following week he returned to New Bern
and bought the house. He remembered bringing

468
00:48:46,550 --> 00:48:50,930
his father around later, showing him what
he was going to do, pointing out the changes

469
00:48:50,930 --> 00:48:57,670
he intended to make. His father seemed weak
as he walked around, coughing and wheezing.

470
00:48:57,670 --> 00:49:02,589
Noah was concerned, but his father told him
not to worry, assuring him that he had the

471
00:49:02,589 --> 00:49:03,589
flu.

472
00:49:03,589 --> 00:49:08,940
Less than one month later his father died
of pneumonia and was buried next to his wife

473
00:49:08,940 --> 00:49:14,951
in the local cemetery. Noah tried to stop
by regularly to leave some flowers; occasionally

474
00:49:14,951 --> 00:49:21,000
he left a note. And every night without fail
he took a moment to remember him, then said

475
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:26,030
a prayer for the man who’d taught him everything
that mattered.

476
00:49:26,030 --> 00:49:31,069
After reeling in the line, he put the gear
away and went back to the house. His neighbor,

477
00:49:31,069 --> 00:49:35,660
Martha Shaw, was there to thank him, bringing
three loaves of homemade bread and some biscuits

478
00:49:35,660 --> 00:49:40,180
in appreciation for what he’d done. Her
husband had been killed in the war, leaving

479
00:49:40,180 --> 00:49:45,280
her with three children and a tired shack
of a house to raise them in. Winter was coming,

480
00:49:45,280 --> 00:49:50,450
and he’d spent a few days at her place last
week repairing her roof, replacing broken

481
00:49:50,450 --> 00:49:55,559
windows and sealing the others, and fixing
her woodstove. Hopefully, it would be enough

482
00:49:55,559 --> 00:49:58,080
to get them through.

483
00:49:58,080 --> 00:50:03,640
Once she’d left, he got in his battered
Dodge truck and went to see Gus. He always

484
00:50:03,640 --> 00:50:08,400
stopped there when he was going to the store
because Gus’s family didn’t have a car.

485
00:50:08,400 --> 00:50:12,160
One of the daughters hopped up and rode with
him, and they did their shopping at Capers

486
00:50:12,160 --> 00:50:17,910
General Store. When he got home he didn’t
unpack the groceries right away. Instead he

487
00:50:17,910 --> 00:50:29,220
showered, found a Budweiser and a book by
Dylan Thomas, and went to sit on the porch.

488
00:50:29,220 --> 00:50:34,750
She still had trouble believing it, even as
she held the proof in her hands.

489
00:50:34,750 --> 00:50:39,349
It had been in the newspaper at her parents’
house three Sundays ago. She had gone to the

490
00:50:39,349 --> 00:50:44,460
kitchen to get a cup of coffee, and when she’d
returned to the table, her father had smiled

491
00:50:44,460 --> 00:50:47,380
and pointed at a small picture. “Remember
this?”

492
00:50:47,380 --> 00:50:54,119
He handed her the paper, and after an uninterested
first glance, something in the picture caught

493
00:50:54,119 --> 00:51:00,739
her eye and she took a closer look. “It
can’t be,” she whispered, and when her

494
00:51:00,739 --> 00:51:05,540
father looked at her curiously, she ignored
him, sat down, and read the article without

495
00:51:05,540 --> 00:51:11,980
speaking. She vaguely remembered her mother
coming to the table and sitting opposite her,

496
00:51:11,980 --> 00:51:16,440
and when she finally put aside the paper,
her mother was staring at her with the same

497
00:51:16,440 --> 00:51:20,170
expression her father had just moments before.

498
00:51:20,170 --> 00:51:27,200
“Are you okay?” her mother asked over
her coffee cup. “You look a little pale.”

499
00:51:27,200 --> 00:51:32,030
She didn’t answer right away, she couldn’t,
and it was then that she’d noticed her hands

500
00:51:32,030 --> 00:51:36,470
were shaking. That had been when it started.

501
00:51:36,470 --> 00:51:45,140
“And here it will end, one way or the other,”
she whispered again. She refolded the scrap

502
00:51:45,140 --> 00:51:49,210
of paper and put it back, remembering that
she had left her parents’ home later that

503
00:51:49,210 --> 00:51:54,370
day with the paper so she could cut out the
article. She read it again before she went

504
00:51:54,370 --> 00:51:59,410
to bed that night, trying to fathom the coincidence,
and read it again the next morning as if to

505
00:51:59,410 --> 00:52:05,920
make sure the whole thing wasn’t a dream.
And now, after three weeks of long walks alone,

506
00:52:05,920 --> 00:52:11,480
after three weeks of distraction, it was the
reason she’d come.

507
00:52:11,480 --> 00:52:18,140
When asked, she said her erratic behavior
was due to stress. It was the perfect excuse;

508
00:52:18,140 --> 00:52:22,140
everyone understood, including Lon, and that’s
why he hadn’t argued when she’d wanted

509
00:52:22,140 --> 00:52:28,460
to get away for a couple of days. The wedding
plans were stressful to everyone involved.

510
00:52:28,460 --> 00:52:33,859
Almost five hundred people were invited, including
the governor, one senator, and the ambassador

511
00:52:33,859 --> 00:52:39,950
to Peru. It was too much, in her opinion,
but their engagement was news and had dominated

512
00:52:39,950 --> 00:52:45,059
the social pages since they had announced
their plans six months ago. Occasionally she

513
00:52:45,059 --> 00:52:50,430
felt like running away with Lon to get married
without the fuss. But she knew he wouldn’t

514
00:52:50,430 --> 00:52:56,990
agree; like the aspiring politician he was,
he loved being the center of attention.

515
00:52:56,990 --> 00:53:03,660
She took a deep breath and stood again. “It’s
now or never,” she whispered, then picked

516
00:53:03,660 --> 00:53:08,930
up her things and went to the door. She paused
only slightly before opening it and going

517
00:53:08,930 --> 00:53:15,099
downstairs. The manager smiled as she walked
by, and she could feel his eyes on her as

518
00:53:15,099 --> 00:53:20,710
she left and went to her car. She slipped
behind the wheel, looked at herself one last

519
00:53:20,710 --> 00:53:25,730
time, then started the engine and turned right
onto Front Street.

520
00:53:25,730 --> 00:53:31,340
She wasn’t surprised that she still knew
her way around town so well. Even though she

521
00:53:31,340 --> 00:53:36,869
hadn’t been here in years, it wasn’t large
and she navigated the streets easily. After

522
00:53:36,869 --> 00:53:41,799
crossing the Trent River on an old-fashioned
drawbridge, she turned onto a gravel road

523
00:53:41,799 --> 00:53:45,990
and began the final leg of her journey.

524
00:53:45,990 --> 00:53:51,710
It was beautiful here in the low country,
as it always had been. Unlike the Piedmont

525
00:53:51,710 --> 00:53:57,309
area where she grew up, the land was flat,
but it had the same silty, fertile soil that

526
00:53:57,309 --> 00:54:04,670
was ideal for cotton and tobacco. Those two
crops and timber kept the towns alive in this

527
00:54:04,670 --> 00:54:09,829
part of the state, and as she drove along
the road outside town, she saw the beauty

528
00:54:09,829 --> 00:54:13,540
that had first attracted people to this region.

529
00:54:13,540 --> 00:54:20,190
To her, it hadn’t changed at all. Broken
sunlight passed through water oaks and hickory

530
00:54:20,190 --> 00:54:27,069
trees a hundred feet tall, illuminating the
colors of fall. On her left, a river the color

531
00:54:27,069 --> 00:54:32,510
of iron veered toward the road and then turned
away before giving up its life to a different,

532
00:54:32,510 --> 00:54:39,369
larger river another mile ahead. The gravel
road itself wound its way between antebellum

533
00:54:39,369 --> 00:54:44,880
farms, and she knew that for some of the farmers,
life hadn’t changed since before their grandparents

534
00:54:44,880 --> 00:54:52,470
were born. The constancy of the place brought
back a flood of memories, and she felt her

535
00:54:52,470 --> 00:55:01,070
insides tighten as one by one she recognized
landmarks she’d long since forgotten.

536
00:55:01,070 --> 00:55:08,380
The sun hung just above the trees on her left,
and as she rounded a curve, she passed an

537
00:55:08,380 --> 00:55:16,180
old church, abandoned for years but still
standing. She had explored it that summer,

538
00:55:16,180 --> 00:55:21,800
looking for souvenirs from the War between
the States, and as her car passed by, the

539
00:55:21,800 --> 00:55:27,450
memories of that day became stronger, as if
they’d just happened yesterday.

540
00:55:27,450 --> 00:55:33,089
A majestic oak tree on the banks of the river
came into view next, and the memories became

541
00:55:33,089 --> 00:55:40,809
more intense. It looked the same as it had
back then, branches low and thick, stretching

542
00:55:40,809 --> 00:55:47,470
horizontally along the ground with Spanish
moss draped over the limbs like a veil. She

543
00:55:47,470 --> 00:55:53,130
remembered sitting beneath the tree on a hot
July day with someone who looked at her with

544
00:55:53,130 --> 00:55:59,780
a longing that took everything else away.
And it had been at that moment that she’d

545
00:55:59,780 --> 00:56:02,530
first fallen in love.

546
00:56:02,530 --> 00:56:09,609
He was two years older than she was, and as
she drove along this roadway-in-time, he slowly

547
00:56:09,609 --> 00:56:16,920
came into focus once again. He always looked
older than he really was, she remembered thinking.

548
00:56:16,920 --> 00:56:22,609
His appearance was that of someone slightly
weathered, almost like a farmer coming home

549
00:56:22,609 --> 00:56:29,240
after hours in the field. He had the callused
hands and broad shoulders that came to those

550
00:56:29,240 --> 00:56:34,760
who worked hard for a living, and the first
faint lines were beginning to form around

551
00:56:34,760 --> 00:56:40,440
the dark eyes that seemed to read her every
thought.

552
00:56:40,440 --> 00:56:48,789
He was tall and strong, with light brown hair,
and handsome in his own way, but it was his

553
00:56:48,789 --> 00:56:55,940
voice that she remembered most of all. He
had read to her that day; read to her as they

554
00:56:55,940 --> 00:57:02,310
lay in the grass beneath the tree with an
accent that was soft and fluent, almost musical

555
00:57:02,310 --> 00:57:09,740
in quality. It was the kind of voice that
belonged on radio, and it seemed to hang in

556
00:57:09,740 --> 00:57:18,079
the air when he read to her. She remembered
closing her eyes, listening closely, and letting

557
00:57:18,079 --> 00:57:24,339
the words he was reading touch her soul:

558
00:57:24,339 --> 00:57:35,109
It coaxes me to the vapor and the dusk.
I depart as air, I shake my white locks at

559
00:57:35,109 --> 00:57:44,270
the runaway sun . . .
He thumbed through old books with dog-eared

560
00:57:44,270 --> 00:57:53,040
pages, books he’d read a hundred times.
He’d read for a while, then stop, and the

561
00:57:53,040 --> 00:57:58,599
two of them would talk. She would tell him
what she wanted in her life— her hopes and

562
00:57:58,599 --> 00:58:04,119
dreams for the future—and he would listen
intently and then promise to make it all come

563
00:58:04,119 --> 00:58:11,859
true. And the way he said it made her believe
him, and she knew then how much he meant to

564
00:58:11,859 --> 00:58:20,329
her. Occasionally, when she asked, he would
talk about himself or explain why he had chosen

565
00:58:20,329 --> 00:58:26,349
a particular poem and what he thought of it,
and at other times he just studied her in

566
00:58:26,349 --> 00:58:29,849
that intense way of his.

567
00:58:29,849 --> 00:58:36,190
They watched the sun go down and ate together
under the stars. It was getting late by then,

568
00:58:36,190 --> 00:58:40,569
and she knew her parents would be furious
if they knew where she was. At that moment,

569
00:58:40,569 --> 00:58:46,770
though, it really didn’t matter to her.
All she could think about was how special

570
00:58:46,770 --> 00:58:52,910
the day had been, how special he was, and
as they started toward her house a few minutes

571
00:58:52,910 --> 00:59:03,750
later, he took her hand in his and she felt
the way it warmed her the whole way back.

572
00:59:03,750 --> 00:59:11,079
Another turn in the road and she finally saw
it in the distance. The house had changed

573
00:59:11,079 --> 00:59:16,970
dramatically from what she remembered. She
slowed the car as she approached, turning

