2564
03:51:25,250 --> 03:51:34,569
And the answer didn’t finally come until
she reached the door and opened it and saw

2565
03:51:34,569 --> 03:51:42,170
Lon standing in the lobby.

2566
03:51:42,170 --> 03:51:47,239
Winter for Two

2567
03:51:47,239 --> 03:51:57,301
The story ends there, so I close the notebook,
remove my glasses, and wipe my eyes. They

2568
03:51:57,301 --> 03:52:05,850
are tired and bloodshot, but they have not
failed me so far. They will soon, I am sure.

2569
03:52:05,850 --> 03:52:14,271
Neither they nor I can go on forever. I look
to her now that I have finished, but she does

2570
03:52:14,271 --> 03:52:20,720
not look back. Instead she is staring out
the window at the courtyard, where friends

2571
03:52:20,720 --> 03:52:23,470
and family meet.

2572
03:52:23,470 --> 03:52:31,070
My eyes follow hers, and we watch it together.
In all these years the daily pattern has not

2573
03:52:31,070 --> 03:52:38,540
changed. Every morning, an hour after breakfast,
they begin to arrive. Young adults, alone

2574
03:52:38,540 --> 03:52:46,120
or with family, come to visit those who live
here. They bring photographs and gifts and

2575
03:52:46,120 --> 03:52:52,199
either sit on the benches or stroll along
the tree-lined paths designed to give a sense

2576
03:52:52,199 --> 03:52:59,320
of nature. Some will stay for the day, but
most leave after a few hours, and when they

2577
03:52:59,320 --> 03:53:08,200
do, I always feel sadness for those they’ve
left behind. I wonder sometimes what my friends

2578
03:53:08,200 --> 03:53:15,659
think as they see their loved ones driving
off, but I know it’s not my business. And

2579
03:53:15,659 --> 03:53:23,310
I do not ever ask them because I’ve learned
that we’re all entitled to have our secrets.

2580
03:53:23,310 --> 03:53:27,340
But soon, I will tell you some of mine.

2581
03:53:27,340 --> 03:53:34,040
I place the notebook and magnifier on the
table beside me, feeling the ache in my bones

2582
03:53:34,040 --> 03:53:42,270
as I do so, and I realize once again how cold
my body is. Even reading in the morning sun

2583
03:53:42,270 --> 03:53:48,560
does nothing to help it. This does not surprise
me anymore, though, for my body makes its

2584
03:53:48,560 --> 03:53:50,659
own rules these days.

2585
03:53:50,659 --> 03:53:58,120
I’m not completely unfortunate, however.
The people who work here know me and my faults

2586
03:53:58,120 --> 03:54:05,100
and do their best to make me more comfortable.
They have left me hot tea on the end table,

2587
03:54:05,100 --> 03:54:10,800
and I reach for it with both hands. It is
an effort to pour a cup, but I do so because

2588
03:54:10,800 --> 03:54:17,149
the tea is needed to warm me and I think the
exertion will keep me from completely rusting

2589
03:54:17,149 --> 03:54:26,570
away. But I am rusted now, no doubt about
it. Rusted as a junked car twenty years in

2590
03:54:26,570 --> 03:54:29,140
the Everglades.

2591
03:54:29,140 --> 03:54:36,319
I have read to her this morning, as I do every
morning, because it is something I must do.

2592
03:54:36,319 --> 03:54:44,060
Not for duty—although I suppose a case could
be made for this—but for another, more romantic,

2593
03:54:44,060 --> 03:54:50,010
reason. I wish I could explain it more fully
right now, but it’s still early, and talking

2594
03:54:50,010 --> 03:54:56,850
about romance isn’t really possible before
lunch anymore, at least not for me. Besides,

2595
03:54:56,850 --> 03:55:02,480
I have no idea how it’s going to turn out,
and to be honest, I’d rather not get my

2596
03:55:02,480 --> 03:55:05,380
hopes up.

2597
03:55:05,380 --> 03:55:12,189
We spend each and every day together now,
but our nights are spent alone. The doctors

2598
03:55:12,189 --> 03:55:17,859
tell me that I’m not allowed to see her
after dark. I understand the reasons completely,

2599
03:55:17,859 --> 03:55:23,779
and though I agree with them, I sometimes
break the rules. Late at night when my mood

2600
03:55:23,779 --> 03:55:31,561
is right, I will sneak from my room and go
to hers and watch her while she sleeps. Of

2601
03:55:31,561 --> 03:55:38,080
this she knows nothing. I’ll come in and
see her breathe and know that had it not been

2602
03:55:38,080 --> 03:55:46,350
for her, I would never have married. And when
I look at her face, a face I know better than

2603
03:55:46,350 --> 03:55:55,460
my own, I know that I have meant as much or
more to her. And that means more to me than

2604
03:55:55,460 --> 03:55:58,220
I could ever hope to explain.

2605
03:55:58,220 --> 03:56:03,850
Sometimes, when I am standing there, I think
about how lucky I am to have been married

2606
03:56:03,850 --> 03:56:11,840
to her for almost forty-nine years. Next month
it will be that long. She heard me snore for

2607
03:56:11,840 --> 03:56:19,120
the first forty-five, but since then we have
slept in separate rooms. I do not sleep well

2608
03:56:19,120 --> 03:56:25,860
without her. I toss and turn and yearn for
her warmth and lie there most of the night,

2609
03:56:25,860 --> 03:56:31,010
eyes open wide, watching the shadows dance
across the ceilings like tumbleweeds rolling

2610
03:56:31,010 --> 03:56:39,000
across the desert. I sleep two hours if I
am lucky, and still I wake before dawn. This

2611
03:56:39,000 --> 03:56:40,660
makes no sense to me.

2612
03:56:40,660 --> 03:56:50,080
Soon, this will all be over. I know this.
She does not. The entries in my diary have

2613
03:56:50,080 --> 03:56:56,920
become shorter and take little time to write.
I keep them simple now, since most of my days

2614
03:56:56,920 --> 03:57:03,930
are the same. But tonight I think I will copy
a poem that one of the nurses found for me

2615
03:57:03,930 --> 03:57:07,460
and thought I would enjoy. It goes like this:

2616
03:57:07,460 --> 03:57:15,560
I ne’er was struck before that hour
With love so sudden and so sweet, Her face

2617
03:57:15,560 --> 03:57:26,290
it bloomed like a sweet flower
And stole my heart away complete.

2618
03:57:26,290 --> 03:57:32,621
Because our evenings are our own, I have been
asked to visit the others. Usually I do, for

2619
03:57:32,621 --> 03:57:40,700
I am the reader and I am needed, or so I am
told. I walk the halls and choose where to

2620
03:57:40,700 --> 03:57:46,960
go because I am too old to devote myself to
a schedule, but deep down I always know who

2621
03:57:46,960 --> 03:57:53,140
needs me. They are my friends, and when I
push open their doors, I see rooms that look

2622
03:57:53,140 --> 03:58:00,061
like mine, always semidarkened, illuminated
only by the lights of Wheel of Fortune and

2623
03:58:00,061 --> 03:58:06,109
Vanna’s teeth. The furniture is the same
for everyone, and the TVs blare because no

2624
03:58:06,109 --> 03:58:09,630
one can hear well anymore.

2625
03:58:09,630 --> 03:58:14,880
Men or women, they smile at me when I enter
and speak in whispers as they turn off their

2626
03:58:14,880 --> 03:58:21,779
sets. “I’m so glad you’ve come,” they
say, and then they ask about my wife. Sometimes

2627
03:58:21,779 --> 03:58:27,210
I tell them. I might tell them of her sweetness
and her charm and describe how she taught

2628
03:58:27,210 --> 03:58:33,561
me to see the world for the beautiful place
it is. Or I tell them of our early years together

2629
03:58:33,561 --> 03:58:39,550
and explain how we had all we needed when
we held each other under starry southern skies.

2630
03:58:39,550 --> 03:58:47,130
On special occasions I whisper of our adventures
together, of art shows in New York and Paris

2631
03:58:47,130 --> 03:58:54,439
or the rave reviews from critics writing in
languages I do not understand. Mostly, though,

2632
03:58:54,439 --> 03:59:01,470
I smile and I tell them that she is the same,
and they turn from me, for I know they do

2633
03:59:01,470 --> 03:59:07,880
not want me to see their faces. It reminds
them of their own mortality. So I sit with

2634
03:59:07,880 --> 03:59:11,159
them and read to lessen their fears.

2635
03:59:11,159 --> 03:59:20,310
Be composed—be at ease with me . . .
Not till the sun excludes you do I exclude

2636
03:59:20,310 --> 03:59:26,850
you, Not till the waters refuse to glisten
for you and the leaves to rustle for you,

2637
03:59:26,850 --> 03:59:32,659
do my words refuse to glisten and rustle for
you.

2638
03:59:32,659 --> 03:59:37,470
And I read, to let them know who I am.

2639
03:59:37,470 --> 03:59:43,840
I wander all night in my vision, . . .
Bending with open eyes over the shut eyes

2640
03:59:43,840 --> 03:59:52,390
of sleepers,
Wandering and confused, lost to myself, ill-assorted,

2641
03:59:52,390 --> 04:00:01,739
contradictory,
Pausing, gazing, bending, and stopping.

2642
04:00:01,739 --> 04:00:07,420
If she could, my wife would accompany me on
my evening excursions, for one of her many

2643
04:00:07,420 --> 04:00:15,750
loves was poetry. Thomas, Whitman, Eliot,
Shakespeare, and King David of the Psalms.

2644
04:00:15,750 --> 04:00:23,540
Lovers of words, makers of language. Looking
back, I am surprised by my passion for it,

2645
04:00:23,540 --> 04:00:31,330
and sometimes I even regret it now. Poetry
brings great beauty to life, but also great

2646
04:00:31,330 --> 04:00:39,640
sadness, and I’m not sure it’s a fair
exchange for someone my age. A man should

2647
04:00:39,640 --> 04:00:48,560
enjoy other things if he can; he should spend
his final days in the sun. Mine will be spent

2648
04:00:48,560 --> 04:00:50,729
by a reading lamp.

2649
04:00:50,729 --> 04:00:59,140
I shuffle toward her and sit in the chair
beside her bed. My back aches when I sit.

2650
04:00:59,140 --> 04:01:06,040
I must get a new cushion for this chair, I
remind myself for the hundredth time. I reach

2651
04:01:06,040 --> 04:01:14,800
for her hand and take it, bony and fragile.
It feels nice. She responds with a twitch,

2652
04:01:14,800 --> 04:01:21,680
and gradually her thumb begins to softly rub
my finger. I do not speak until she does;

2653
04:01:21,680 --> 04:01:27,949
this I have learned. Most days I sit in silence
until the sun goes down, and on days like

2654
04:01:27,949 --> 04:01:31,870
those I know nothing about her.

2655
04:01:31,870 --> 04:01:39,630
Minutes pass before she finally turns to me.
She is crying. I smile and release her hand,

2656
04:01:39,630 --> 04:01:46,100
then reach in my pocket. I take out a handkerchief
and wipe at her tears. She looks at me as

2657
04:01:46,100 --> 04:01:49,870
I do so, and I wonder what she is thinking.

2658
04:01:49,870 --> 04:01:53,979
“That was a beautiful story.”

2659
04:01:53,979 --> 04:02:01,300
A light rain begins to fall. Little drops
tap gently on the window. I take her hand

2660
04:02:01,300 --> 04:02:08,600
again. It is going to be a good day, a very
good day. A magical day. I smile, I can’t

2661
04:02:08,600 --> 04:02:09,880
help it.

2662
04:02:09,880 --> 04:02:13,250
“Yes, it is,” I tell her.

2663
04:02:13,250 --> 04:02:21,220
“Did you write it?” she asks. Her voice
is like a whisper, a light wind flowing through

2664
04:02:21,220 --> 04:02:22,740
the leaves.

2665
04:02:22,740 --> 04:02:26,359
“Yes,” I answer.

2666
04:02:26,359 --> 04:02:32,350
She turns toward the nightstand. Her medicine
is in a little cup. Mine too. Little pills,

2667
04:02:32,350 --> 04:02:37,810
colors like a rainbow so we won’t forget
to take them. They bring mine here now, to

2668
04:02:37,810 --> 04:02:40,380
her room, even though they’re not supposed
to.

2669
04:02:40,380 --> 04:02:45,859
“I’ve heard it before, haven’t I?”

2670
04:02:45,859 --> 04:02:51,760
“Yes,” I say again, just as I do every
time on days like these. I have learned to

2671
04:02:51,760 --> 04:02:54,130
be patient.

2672
04:02:54,130 --> 04:02:59,840
She studies my face. Her eyes are as green
as ocean waves.

2673
04:02:59,840 --> 04:03:05,210
“It makes me feel less afraid,” she says.

2674
04:03:05,210 --> 04:03:11,640
“I know.” I nod, rocking my head softly.

2675
04:03:11,640 --> 04:03:17,850
She turns away, and I wait some more. She
releases my hand and reaches for her water

2676
04:03:17,850 --> 04:03:22,720
glass. It is on her nightstand, next to the
medicine. She takes a sip.

2677
04:03:22,720 --> 04:03:31,220
“Is it a true story?” She sits up a little
in her bed and takes another drink. Her body

2678
04:03:31,220 --> 04:03:37,200
is still strong. “I mean, did you know these
people?”

2679
04:03:37,200 --> 04:03:45,100
“Yes,” I say again. I could say more,
but usually I don’t. She is still beautiful.

2680
04:03:45,100 --> 04:03:46,729
She asks the obvious:

2681
04:03:46,729 --> 04:03:52,310
“Well, which one did she finally marry?”

2682
04:03:52,310 --> 04:04:00,000
I answer: “The one who was right for her.”
“Which one was that?”

2683
04:04:00,000 --> 04:04:11,609
I smile. “You’ll know,” I say quietly,
“by the end of the day. You’ll know.”

2684
04:04:11,609 --> 04:04:15,841
She does not know what to think about this
but does not question me further. Instead

2685
04:04:15,841 --> 04:04:21,260
she begins to fidget. She is thinking of a
way to ask me another question, though she

2686
04:04:21,260 --> 04:04:28,340
isn’t sure how to do it. Instead she chooses
to put it off for a moment and reaches for

2687
04:04:28,340 --> 04:04:30,370
one of the little paper cups.

2688
04:04:30,370 --> 04:04:32,979
“Is this mine?”

2689
04:04:32,979 --> 04:04:40,830
“No, this one is,” and I reach over and
push her medicine toward her. I cannot grab

2690
04:04:40,830 --> 04:04:48,010
it with my fingers. She takes it and looks
at the pills. I can tell by the way she is

2691
04:04:48,010 --> 04:04:55,229
looking at them that she has no idea what
they are for. I use both hands to pick up

2692
04:04:55,229 --> 04:05:02,710
my cup and dump the pills into my mouth. She
does the same. There is no fight today. That

2693
04:05:02,710 --> 04:05:10,430
makes it easy. I raise my cup in a mock toast
and wash the gritty flavor from my mouth with

2694
04:05:10,430 --> 04:05:19,660
my tea. It is getting colder. She swallows
on faith and washes them down with more water.

2695
04:05:19,660 --> 04:05:25,850
A bird starts to sing outside the window,
and we both turn our heads. We sit quietly

2696
04:05:25,850 --> 04:05:32,449
for a while, enjoying something beautiful
together. Then it is lost, and she sighs.

2697
04:05:32,449 --> 04:05:41,310
“I have to ask you something else,” she
says. “Whatever it is, I’ll try to answer.”

2698
04:05:41,310 --> 04:05:44,560
“It’s hard, though.”

2699
04:05:44,560 --> 04:05:50,090
She does not look at me, and I cannot see
her eyes. This is how she hides her thoughts.

2700
04:05:50,090 --> 04:05:52,540
Some things never change.

2701
04:05:52,540 --> 04:06:01,500
“Take your time,” I say. I know what she
will ask. Finally she turns to me and looks

2702
04:06:01,500 --> 04:06:09,350
into my eyes. She offers a gentle smile, the
kind you share with a child, not a lover.

2703
04:06:09,350 --> 04:06:16,880
“I don’t want to hurt your feelings because
you’ve been so nice to me, but . . .”

2704
04:06:16,880 --> 04:06:27,790
I wait. Her words will hurt me. They will
tear a piece from my heart and leave a scar.

2705
04:06:27,790 --> 04:06:36,949
“Who are you?”

2706
04:06:36,949 --> 04:06:42,840
We have lived at Creekside Extended Care Facility
for three years now. It was her decision to

2707
04:06:42,840 --> 04:06:47,779
come here, partly because it was near our
home, but also because she thought it would

2708
04:06:47,779 --> 04:06:54,330
be easier for me. We boarded up our home because
neither of us could bear to sell it, signed

2709
04:06:54,330 --> 04:07:00,460
some papers, and just like that we received
a place to live and die in exchange for some

2710
04:07:00,460 --> 04:07:04,060
of the freedom for which we had worked a lifetime.

2711
04:07:04,060 --> 04:07:09,729
She was right to do this, of course. There
is no way I could have made it alone, for

2712
04:07:09,729 --> 04:07:16,630
sickness has come to us, both of us. We are
in the final minutes in the day of our lives,

2713
04:07:16,630 --> 04:07:21,949
and the clock is ticking. Loudly. I wonder
if I am the only one who can hear it.

2714
04:07:21,949 --> 04:07:27,930
A throbbing pain courses through my fingers,
and it reminds me that we have not held hands

2715
04:07:27,930 --> 04:07:35,310
with fingers interlocked since we moved here.
I am sad about this, but it is my fault, not

2716
04:07:35,310 --> 04:07:45,950
hers. It is arthritis in the worst form, rheumatoid
and advanced. My hands are misshapen and grotesque

2717
04:07:45,950 --> 04:07:53,100
now, and they throb during most of my waking
hours. I look at them and want them gone,

2718
04:07:53,100 --> 04:07:58,080
amputated, but then I would not be able to
do the little things I must do. So I use my

2719
04:07:58,080 --> 04:08:04,600
claws, as I call them sometimes, and every
day I take her hands despite the pain, and

2720
04:08:04,600 --> 04:08:11,060
I do my best to hold them because that is
what she wants me to do.

2721
04:08:11,060 --> 04:08:17,060
Although the Bible says man can live to be
120, I don’t want to, and I don’t think

2722
04:08:17,060 --> 04:08:25,290
my body would make it even if I did. It is
falling apart, dying one piece at a time,

2723
04:08:25,290 --> 04:08:31,630
steady erosion on the inside and at the joints.
My hands are useless, my kidneys are beginning

2724
04:08:31,630 --> 04:08:38,750
to fail, and my heart rate is decreasing every
month. Worse, I have cancer again, this time

2725
04:08:38,750 --> 04:08:46,080
of the prostate. This is my third bout with
the unseen enemy, and it will take me eventually,

2726
04:08:46,080 --> 04:08:53,000
though not till I say it is time. The doctors
are worried about me, but I am not. I have

2727
04:08:53,000 --> 04:08:58,250
no time for worry in this twilight of my life.

2728
04:08:58,250 --> 04:09:02,739
Of our five children, four are still living,
and though it is hard for them to visit, they

2729
04:09:02,739 --> 04:09:08,000
come often, and for this I am thankful. But
even when they aren’t here, they come alive

2730
04:09:08,000 --> 04:09:13,670
in my mind every day, each of them, and they
bring to mind the smiles and tears that come

2731
04:09:13,670 --> 04:09:20,510
with raising a family. A dozen pictures line
the walls of my room. They are my heritage,

2732
04:09:20,510 --> 04:09:27,060
my contribution to the world. I am very proud.
Sometimes I wonder what my wife thinks of

2733
04:09:27,060 --> 04:09:33,630
them as she dreams, or if she thinks of them
at all, or if she even dreams. There is so

2734
04:09:33,630 --> 04:09:38,210
much about her I don’t understand anymore.

2735
04:09:38,210 --> 04:09:43,989
I wonder what my daddy would think of my life
and what he would do if he were me. I have

2736
04:09:43,989 --> 04:09:49,909
not seen him for fifty years and he is now
but a shadow in my thoughts. I cannot picture

2737
04:09:49,909 --> 04:09:57,220
him clearly anymore; his face is darkened
as if a light shines from behind him. I am

2738
04:09:57,220 --> 04:10:02,790
not sure if this is due to a failing memory
or simply the passage of time. I have only

2739
04:10:02,790 --> 04:10:09,100
one picture of him, and this too has faded.
In another ten years it will be gone and so

2740
04:10:09,100 --> 04:10:16,330
will I, and his memory will be erased like
a message in the sand. If not for my diaries,

2741
04:10:16,330 --> 04:10:22,189
I would swear I had lived only half as long
as I have. Long periods of my life seem to

2742
04:10:22,189 --> 04:10:29,319
have vanished. And even now I read the passages
and wonder who I was when I wrote them, for

2743
04:10:29,319 --> 04:10:36,609
I cannot remember the events of my life. There
are times I sit and wonder where it all has

2744
04:10:36,609 --> 04:10:38,670
gone.

2745
04:10:38,670 --> 04:10:49,550
“My name,” I say, “is Duke.” I have
always been a John Wayne fan.

2746
04:10:49,550 --> 04:10:58,369
“Duke,” she whispers to herself, “Duke.”
She thinks for a moment, her forehead wrinkled,

2747
04:10:58,369 --> 04:11:00,490
her eyes serious.

2748
04:11:00,490 --> 04:11:08,870
“Yes,” I say, “I’m here for you.”
And always will be, I think to myself.

2749
04:11:08,870 --> 04:11:15,760
She flushes with my answer. Her eyes become
wet and red, and tears begin to fall. My heart

2750
04:11:15,760 --> 04:11:22,279
aches for her, and I wish for the thousandth
time that there was something I could do.

2751
04:11:22,279 --> 04:11:23,350
She says:

2752
04:11:23,350 --> 04:11:31,200
“I’m sorry. I don’t understand anything
that’s happening to me right now. Even you.

2753
04:11:31,200 --> 04:11:36,869
When I listen to you talk I feel like I should
know you, but I don’t. I don’t even know

2754
04:11:36,869 --> 04:11:39,930
my name.”

2755
04:11:39,930 --> 04:11:49,529
She wipes at her tears and says, “Help me,
Duke, help me remember who I am. Or at least,

2756
04:11:49,529 --> 04:11:55,710
who I was. I feel so lost.”

2757
04:11:55,710 --> 04:12:04,310
I answer from my heart, but I lie to her about
her name. As I have about my own. There is

2758
04:12:04,310 --> 04:12:06,140
a reason for this.

2759
04:12:06,140 --> 04:12:15,540
“You are Hannah, a lover of life, a strength
to those who shared in your friendships. You

2760
04:12:15,540 --> 04:12:23,350
are a dream, a creator of happiness, an artist
who has touched a thousand souls. You’ve

2761
04:12:23,350 --> 04:12:29,090
led a full life and wanted for nothing because
your needs are spiritual and you have only

2762
04:12:29,090 --> 04:12:35,810
to look inside you. You are kind and loyal,
and you are able to see beauty where others

2763
04:12:35,810 --> 04:12:46,390
do not. You are a teacher of wonderful lessons,
a dreamer of better things.”

2764
04:12:46,390 --> 04:12:54,819
I stop for a moment and catch my breath. Then,
“Hannah, there is no reason to feel lost,

2765
04:12:54,819 --> 04:12:56,430
for:

2766
04:12:56,430 --> 04:13:06,060
Nothing is ever really lost, or can be lost,
No birth, identity, form—no object of the

2767
04:13:06,060 --> 04:13:13,340
world,
Nor life, nor force, nor any visible thing;

2768
04:13:13,340 --> 04:13:18,050
. . . The body, sluggish, aged, cold—the
embers left from earlier fires,

2769
04:13:18,050 --> 04:13:28,560
. . . shall duly flame again;”
She thinks about what I have said for a moment.

2770
04:13:28,560 --> 04:13:33,831
In the silence, I look toward the window and
notice that the rain has stopped now. Sunlight

2771
04:13:33,831 --> 04:13:37,479
is beginning to filter into her room. She
asks:

2772
04:13:37,479 --> 04:13:40,689
“Did you write that?”

2773
04:13:40,689 --> 04:13:44,450
“No, that was Walt Whitman.” “Who?”

2774
04:13:44,450 --> 04:13:51,040
“A lover of words, a shaper of thoughts.”

2775
04:13:51,040 --> 04:13:58,680
She does not respond directly. Instead she
stares at me for a long while, until our breathing

2776
04:13:58,680 --> 04:14:17,150
coincides. In. Out. In. Out. In. Out. Deep
breaths. I wonder if she knows I think she’s

2777
04:14:17,150 --> 04:14:18,300
beautiful.

2778
04:14:18,300 --> 04:14:24,420
“Would you stay with me a while?” she
finally asks.

2779
04:14:24,420 --> 04:14:33,130
I smile and nod. She smiles back. She reaches
for my hand, takes it gently, and pulls it

2780
04:14:33,130 --> 04:14:42,649
to her waist. She stares at the hardened knots
that deform my fingers and caresses them gently.

2781
04:14:42,649 --> 04:14:46,460
Her hands are still those of an angel.

2782
04:14:46,460 --> 04:14:54,659
“Come,” I say as I stand with great effort,
“let’s go for a walk. The air is crisp

2783
04:14:54,659 --> 04:15:01,751
and the goslings are waiting. It’s beautiful
today.” I am staring at her as I say these

2784
04:15:01,751 --> 04:15:04,350
last few words.

2785
04:15:04,350 --> 04:15:12,890
She blushes. It makes me feel young again.

2786
04:15:12,890 --> 04:15:19,319
She was famous, of course. One of the best
southern painters of the twentieth century,

2787
04:15:19,319 --> 04:15:26,649
some said, and I was, and am, proud of her.
Unlike me, who struggled to write even the

2788
04:15:26,649 --> 04:15:34,720
simplest of verses, my wife could create beauty
as easily as the Lord created the earth. Her

2789
04:15:34,720 --> 04:15:40,810
paintings are in museums around the world,
but I have kept only two for myself. The first

2790
04:15:40,810 --> 04:15:47,279
one she ever gave me and the last one. They
hang in my room, and late at night I sit and

2791
04:15:47,279 --> 04:15:54,070
stare and sometimes cry when I look at them.
I don’t know why.

2792
04:15:54,070 --> 04:16:00,909
And so the years passed. We led our lives,
working, painting, raising children, loving

2793
04:16:00,909 --> 04:16:09,520
each other. I see photos of Christmases, family
trips, of graduations and of weddings. I see

2794
04:16:09,520 --> 04:16:15,130
grandchildren and happy faces. I see photos
of us, our hair growing whiter, the lines

2795
04:16:15,130 --> 04:16:23,000
in our faces deeper. A lifetime that seems
so typical, yet uncommon.

2796
04:16:23,000 --> 04:16:30,140
We could not foresee the future, but then
who can? I do not live now as I expected to.

2797
04:16:30,140 --> 04:16:37,220
And what did I expect? Retirement. Visits
with the grandchildren, perhaps more travel.

2798
04:16:37,220 --> 04:16:43,391
She always loved to travel. I thought that
perhaps I would start a hobby, what I did

2799
04:16:43,391 --> 04:16:50,760
not know, but possibly shipbuilding. In bottles.
Small, detailed, impossible to consider now

2800
04:16:50,760 --> 04:16:55,850
with my hands. But I am not bitter.

2801
04:16:55,850 --> 04:17:00,930
Our lives can’t be measured by our final
years, of this I am sure, and I guess I should

2802
04:17:00,930 --> 04:17:07,270
have known what lay ahead in our lives. Looking
back, I suppose it seems obvious, but at first

2803
04:17:07,270 --> 04:17:13,080
I thought her confusion understandable and
not unique. She would forget where she placed

2804
04:17:13,080 --> 04:17:19,350
her keys, but who has not done that? She would
forget a neighbor’s name, but not someone

2805
04:17:19,350 --> 04:17:25,790
we knew well or with whom we socialized. Sometimes
she would write the wrong year when she made

2806
04:17:25,790 --> 04:17:31,479
out her checks, but again I dismissed it as
simple mistakes that one makes when thinking

2807
04:17:31,479 --> 04:17:34,710
of other things.

2808
04:17:34,710 --> 04:17:41,310
It was not until the more obvious events occurred
that I began to suspect the worst. An iron

2809
04:17:41,310 --> 04:17:48,260
in the freezer, clothes in the dishwasher,
books in the oven. Other things, too. But

2810
04:17:48,260 --> 04:17:53,380
the day I found her in the car three blocks
away, crying over the steering wheel because

2811
04:17:53,380 --> 04:17:59,380
she couldn’t find her way home was the first
day I was really frightened. And she was frightened,

2812
04:17:59,380 --> 04:18:04,760
too, for when I tapped on her window, she
turned to me and said, “Oh God, what’s

2813
04:18:04,760 --> 04:18:10,680
happening to me? Please help me.” A knot
twisted in my stomach, but I dared not think

2814
04:18:10,680 --> 04:18:13,500
the worst.

2815
04:18:13,500 --> 04:18:19,180
Six days later the doctor met with her and
began a series of tests. I did not understand

2816
04:18:19,180 --> 04:18:25,300
them then and I do not understand them now,
but I suppose it is because I am afraid to

2817
04:18:25,300 --> 04:18:33,199
know. She spent almost an hour with Dr. Barnwell,
and she went back the next day. That day was

2818
04:18:33,199 --> 04:18:39,739
the longest day I ever spent. I looked through
magazines I could not read and played games

2819
04:18:39,739 --> 04:18:46,020
I did not think about. Finally he called us
both into his office and sat us down. She

2820
04:18:46,020 --> 04:18:51,350
held my arm confidently, but I remember clearly
that my own hands were shaking.

2821
04:18:51,350 --> 04:18:56,810
“I’m so sorry to have to tell you this,”
Dr. Barn-well began, “but you seem to be

2822
04:18:56,810 --> 04:19:00,440
in the early stages of Alzheimer’s. . . .”

2823
04:19:00,440 --> 04:19:06,580
My mind went blank, and all I could think
about was the light that glowed above our

2824
04:19:06,580 --> 04:19:12,420
heads. The words echoed in my head: the early
stages of Alzheimer’s . . .

2825
04:19:12,420 --> 04:19:20,560
My world spun in circles, and I felt her grip
tighten on my arm. She whispered, almost to

2826
04:19:20,560 --> 04:19:24,430
herself: “Oh, Noah . . . Noah . . .”

2827
04:19:24,430 --> 04:19:31,979
And as the tears started to fall, the word
came back to me again: . . . Alzheimer’s

2828
04:19:31,979 --> 04:19:32,979
...

2829
04:19:32,979 --> 04:19:39,690
It is a barren disease, as empty and lifeless
as a desert. It is a thief of hearts and souls

2830
04:19:39,690 --> 04:19:46,050
and memories. I did not know what to say to
her as she sobbed on my bosom, so I simply

2831
04:19:46,050 --> 04:19:49,060
held her and rocked her back and forth.

2832
04:19:49,060 --> 04:19:55,430
The doctor was grim. He was a good man, and
this was hard for him. He was younger than

2833
04:19:55,430 --> 04:20:03,390
my youngest, and I felt my age in his presence.
My mind was confused, my love was shaking,

2834
04:20:03,390 --> 04:20:07,060
and the only thing I could think was:

2835
04:20:07,060 --> 04:20:16,390
No drowning man can know which drop of water
his last breath did stop; . . .

2836
04:20:16,390 --> 04:20:23,060
A wise poet’s words, yet they brought me
no comfort. I don’t know what they meant

2837
04:20:23,060 --> 04:20:26,500
or why I thought of them.

2838
04:20:26,500 --> 04:20:35,850
We rocked to and fro, and Allie, my dream,
my timeless beauty, told me she was sorry.

2839
04:20:35,850 --> 04:20:40,470
I knew there was nothing to forgive, and I
whispered in her ear. “Everything will be

2840
04:20:40,470 --> 04:20:47,210
fine,” I whispered, but inside I was afraid.
I was a hollow man with nothing to offer,

2841
04:20:47,210 --> 04:20:51,560
empty as a junked stovepipe.

2842
04:20:51,560 --> 04:20:56,760
I remember only bits and pieces of Dr. Barnwell’s
continuing explanation.

2843
04:20:56,760 --> 04:21:04,260
“It’s a degenerative brain disorder affecting
memory and personality . . . there is no cure

2844
04:21:04,260 --> 04:21:05,260
or therapy. . . .

2845
04:21:05,260 --> 04:21:11,580
There’s no way to tell how fast it will
progress . . . it differs from person to person.

2846
04:21:11,580 --> 04:21:13,600
...I wish I knew more. . . .

2847
04:21:13,600 --> 04:21:18,689
Some days will be better than others. ...It
will grow worse with the passage of time.

2848
04:21:18,689 --> 04:21:21,930
. . . I’m sorry to be the one who has to
tell you. . . .”

2849
04:21:21,930 --> 04:21:24,439
I’m sorry . . .
I’m sorry . . .

2850
04:21:24,439 --> 04:21:32,670
I’m sorry . . .
Everyone was sorry. My children were broken-hearted,

2851
04:21:32,670 --> 04:21:39,010
my friends were scared for themselves. I don’t
remember leaving the doctor’s office, and

2852
04:21:39,010 --> 04:21:46,199
I don’t remember driving home. My memories
of that day are gone, and in this my wife

2853
04:21:46,199 --> 04:21:47,560
and I are the same.

2854
04:21:47,560 --> 04:21:55,590
It has been four years now. Since then we
have made the best of it, if that is possible.

2855
04:21:55,590 --> 04:22:01,000
Allie organized, as was her disposition. She
made arrangements to leave the house and move

2856
04:22:01,000 --> 04:22:08,260
here. She rewrote her will and sealed it.
She left specific burial instructions, and

2857
04:22:08,260 --> 04:22:15,850
they sit in my desk, in the bottom drawer.
I have not seen them. And when she was finished,

2858
04:22:15,850 --> 04:22:21,460
she began to write. Letters to friends and
children. Letters to brothers and sisters

2859
04:22:21,460 --> 04:22:30,140
and cousins. Letters to nieces, nephews, and
neighbors. And a letter to me.

2860
04:22:30,140 --> 04:22:36,449
I read it sometimes when I am in the mood,
and when I do, I am reminded of Allie on cold

2861
04:22:36,449 --> 04:22:42,431
winter evenings, seated by a roaring fire
with a glass of wine at her side, reading

2862
04:22:42,431 --> 04:22:48,479
the letters I had written to her over the
years. She kept them, these letters, and now

2863
04:22:48,479 --> 04:22:53,869
I keep them, for she made me promise to do
so. She said I would know what to do with

2864
04:22:53,869 --> 04:23:01,050
them. She was right; I find I enjoy reading
bits and pieces of them just as she used to.

2865
04:23:01,050 --> 04:23:06,159
They intrigue me, these letters, for when
I sift through them I realize that romance

2866
04:23:06,159 --> 04:23:14,590
and passion are possible at any age. I see
Allie now and know I’ve never loved her

2867
04:23:14,590 --> 04:23:21,109
more, but as I read the letters, I come to
understand that I have always felt the same

2868
04:23:21,109 --> 04:23:23,330
way.

2869
04:23:23,330 --> 04:23:28,520
I read them last three evenings ago, long
after I should have been asleep. It was almost

2870
04:23:28,520 --> 04:23:32,989
two o’clock when I went to the desk and
found the stack of letters, thick and tall

2871
04:23:32,989 --> 04:23:39,640
and weathered. I untied the ribbon, itself
almost half a century old, and found the letters

2872
04:23:39,640 --> 04:23:45,751
her mother had hidden so long ago and those
from afterward. A lifetime of letters, letters

2873
04:23:45,751 --> 04:23:52,180
professing my love, letters from my heart.
I glanced through them with a smile on my

2874
04:23:52,180 --> 04:23:58,630
face, picking and choosing, and finally opened
a letter from our first anniversary.

2875
04:23:58,630 --> 04:24:00,880
I read an excerpt:

2876
04:24:00,880 --> 04:24:08,449
When I see you now—moving slowly with new
life growing inside you—I hope you know

2877
04:24:08,449 --> 04:24:16,250
how much you mean to me, and how special this
year has been. No man is more blessed than

2878
04:24:16,250 --> 04:24:25,189
me, and I love you with all my heart.
I put it aside, sifted through the stack,

2879
04:24:25,189 --> 04:24:32,020
and found another, this from a cold evening
thirty-nine years ago.

2880
04:24:32,020 --> 04:24:38,890
Sitting next to you, while our youngest daughter
sang off-key in the school Christmas show,

2881
04:24:38,890 --> 04:24:46,550
I looked at you and saw a pride that comes
only to those who feel deeply in their hearts,

2882
04:24:46,550 --> 04:24:54,140
and I knew that no man could be more lucky
than me.

2883
04:24:54,140 --> 04:24:59,029
And after our son died, the one who resembled
his mother . . . It was the hardest time we

2884
04:24:59,029 --> 04:25:04,430
ever went through, and the words still ring
true today:

2885
04:25:04,430 --> 04:25:10,680
In times of grief and sorrow I will hold you
and rock you, and take your grief and make

2886
04:25:10,680 --> 04:25:18,810
it my own. When you cry, I cry, and when you
hurt, I hurt. And together we will try to

2887
04:25:18,810 --> 04:25:25,320
hold back the floods of tears and despair
and make it through the potholed streets of

2888
04:25:25,320 --> 04:25:32,560
life.
I pause for just a moment, remembering him.

2889
04:25:32,560 --> 04:25:37,810
He was four years old at the time, just a
baby. I have lived twenty times as long as

2890
04:25:37,810 --> 04:25:44,570
he, but if asked, I would have traded my life
for his. It is a terrible thing to outlive

2891
04:25:44,570 --> 04:25:49,840
your child, a tragedy I wish upon no one.

2892
04:25:49,840 --> 04:25:55,390
I do my best to keep the tears away, sift
through some more to clear my mind, and find

2893
04:25:55,390 --> 04:26:01,771
the next from our twentieth anniversary, something
much easier to think about:

2894
04:26:01,771 --> 04:26:07,279
When I see you, my darling, in the morning
before showers or in your studio covered with

2895
04:26:07,279 --> 04:26:14,100
paint with hair matted and tired eyes, I know
that you are the most beautiful woman in the

2896
04:26:14,100 --> 04:26:19,680
world.
They went on, this correspondence of life

2897
04:26:19,680 --> 04:26:27,260
and love, and I read dozens more, some painful,
most heartwarming. By three o’clock I was

2898
04:26:27,260 --> 04:26:32,410
tired, but I had reached the bottom of the
stack. There was one letter remaining, the

2899
04:26:32,410 --> 04:26:37,470
last one I wrote her, and by then I knew I
had to keep going.

2900
04:26:37,470 --> 04:26:44,949
I lifted the seal and removed both pages.
I put the second page aside and moved the

2901
04:26:44,949 --> 04:26:48,529
first page into better light and began to
read:

2902
04:26:48,529 --> 04:26:54,430
My dearest Allie,
The porch is silent except for the sounds

2903
04:26:54,430 --> 04:27:01,250
that float from the shadows, and for once
I am at a loss for words. It is a strange

2904
04:27:01,250 --> 04:27:06,010
experience for me, for when I think of you
and the life we have shared, there is much

2905
04:27:06,010 --> 04:27:14,300
to remember. A lifetime of memories. But to
put it into words? I do not know if I am able.

2906
04:27:14,300 --> 04:27:21,340
I am not a poet, and yet a poem is needed
to fully express the way I feel about you.

2907
04:27:21,340 --> 04:27:26,790
So my mind drifts, and I remember thinking
about our life together as I made coffee this

2908
04:27:26,790 --> 04:27:33,170
morning. Kate was there, and so was Jane,
and they both became quiet when I walked in

2909
04:27:33,170 --> 04:27:39,550
the kitchen. I saw they’d been crying, and
without a word, I sat myself beside them at

2910
04:27:39,550 --> 04:27:46,470
the table and held their hands. And do you
know what I saw when I looked at them? I saw

2911
04:27:46,470 --> 04:27:55,660
you from so long ago, the day we said good-bye.
They resemble you and how you were then, beautiful

2912
04:27:55,660 --> 04:28:03,140
and sensitive and wounded with the hurt that
comes when something special is taken away.

2913
04:28:03,140 --> 04:28:10,350
And for a reason I’m not sure I understand,
I was inspired to tell them a story.

2914
04:28:10,350 --> 04:28:16,260
I called Jeff and David into the kitchen,
for they were here as well, and when the children

2915
04:28:16,260 --> 04:28:22,689
were ready, I told them about us and how you
came back to me so long ago. I told them about

2916
04:28:22,689 --> 04:28:28,319
our walk, and the crab dinner in the kitchen,
and they listened with smiles when they heard

2917
04:28:28,319 --> 04:28:34,220
about the canoe ride, and sitting in front
of the fire with the storm raging outside.

2918
04:28:34,220 --> 04:28:40,550
I told them about your mother warning us about
Lon the next day—they seemed as surprised

2919
04:28:40,550 --> 04:28:45,609
as we were—and yes, I even told them what
happened later that day, after you went back

2920
04:28:45,609 --> 04:28:50,880
to town.
That part of the story has never left me,

2921
04:28:50,880 --> 04:28:56,300
even after all this time. Even though I wasn’t
there, you described it to me only once, and

2922
04:28:56,300 --> 04:29:02,070
I remember marveling at the strength you showed
that day. I still cannot imagine what was

2923
04:29:02,070 --> 04:29:06,899
going through your mind when you walked into
the lobby and saw Lon, or how it must have

2924
04:29:06,899 --> 04:29:12,320
felt to talk to him. You told me that the
two of you left the inn and sat on a bench

2925
04:29:12,320 --> 04:29:18,070
by the old Methodist church, and that he held
your hand, even as you explained that you

2926
04:29:18,070 --> 04:29:22,819
must stay.
I know you cared for him. And his reaction

2927
04:29:22,819 --> 04:29:29,290
proves to me he cared for you as well. No,
he could not understand losing you, but how

2928
04:29:29,290 --> 04:29:34,760
could he? Even as you explained that you had
always loved me, and that it wouldn’t be

2929
04:29:34,760 --> 04:29:40,159
fair to him, he
did not release your hand. I know he was hurt

2930
04:29:40,159 --> 04:29:46,640
and angry, and tried for almost an hour to
change your mind, but when you stood firm

2931
04:29:46,640 --> 04:29:52,040
and said, “I can’t go back with you, I’m
so sorry,” he knew that your decision had

2932
04:29:52,040 --> 04:29:58,189
been made. You said he simply nodded and the
two of you sat together for a long time without

2933
04:29:58,189 --> 04:30:04,460
speaking. I have always wondered what he was
thinking as he sat with you, but I’m sure

2934
04:30:04,460 --> 04:30:10,260
it was the same way I felt only a few hours
before. And when he finally walked you to

2935
04:30:10,260 --> 04:30:19,370
your car, you said he told you that I was
a lucky man. He behaved as a gentleman would,

2936
04:30:19,370 --> 04:30:23,350
and I understood then why your choice was
so hard.

2937
04:30:23,350 --> 04:30:28,819
I remember that when I finished the story,
the room was quiet until Kate finally stood

2938
04:30:28,819 --> 04:30:35,689
to embrace me. “Oh, Daddy,” she said with
tears in her eyes, and though I expected to

2939
04:30:35,689 --> 04:30:42,470
answer their questions, they did not ask any.
Instead, they gave me something much more

2940
04:30:42,470 --> 04:30:47,260
special.
For the next four hours, each of them told

2941
04:30:47,260 --> 04:30:54,569
me how much we, the two of us, had meant to
them growing up. One by one, they told stories

2942
04:30:54,569 --> 04:31:02,010
about things I had long since forgotten. And
by the end, I was crying because I realized

2943
04:31:02,010 --> 04:31:09,979
how well we had done with raising them. I
was so proud of them, and proud of you, and

2944
04:31:09,979 --> 04:31:17,420
happy about the life we have led. And nothing
will ever take that away. Nothing. I only

2945
04:31:17,420 --> 04:31:23,260
wish you would have been here to enjoy it
with me.

2946
04:31:23,260 --> 04:31:29,069
After they left, I rocked in silence, thinking
back on our life together. You are always

2947
04:31:29,069 --> 04:31:35,479
here with me when I do so, at least in my
heart, and it is impossible for me to remember

2948
04:31:35,479 --> 04:31:42,760
a time when you were not a part of me. I do
not know who I would have become had you never

2949
04:31:42,760 --> 04:31:49,649
come back to me that day, but I have no doubt
that I would have lived and died with regrets

2950
04:31:49,649 --> 04:31:57,930
that thankfully I’ll never know.
I love you, Allie. I am who I am because of

2951
04:31:57,930 --> 04:32:05,510
you. You are every reason, every hope, and
every dream I’ve ever had, and no matter

2952
04:32:05,510 --> 04:32:12,220
what happens to us in the future, every day
we are together is the greatest day of my

2953
04:32:12,220 --> 04:32:21,640
life. I will always be yours.
And, my darling, you will always be mine.

2954
04:32:21,640 --> 04:32:30,560
Noah
I put the pages aside and remember sitting

2955
04:32:30,560 --> 04:32:37,580
with Allie on our porch when she read this
letter for the first time. It was late afternoon,

2956
04:32:37,580 --> 04:32:43,689
with red streaks cutting the summer sky, and
the last remnants of the day were fading.

2957
04:32:43,689 --> 04:32:49,931
The sky was slowly changing color, and as
I was watching the sun go down, I remember

2958
04:32:49,931 --> 04:32:56,590
thinking about that brief, flickering moment
when day suddenly turns into night.

2959
04:32:56,590 --> 04:33:04,529
Dusk, I realized then, is just an illusion,
because the sun is either above the horizon

2960
04:33:04,529 --> 04:33:12,230
or below it. And that means that day and night
are linked in a way that few things are; there

2961
04:33:12,230 --> 04:33:20,459
cannot be one without the other, yet they
cannot exist at the same time. How would it

2962
04:33:20,459 --> 04:33:29,721
feel, I remember wondering, to be always together,
yet forever apart?

2963
04:33:29,721 --> 04:33:34,480
Looking back, I find it ironic that she chose
to read the letter at the exact moment that

2964
04:33:34,480 --> 04:33:42,311
question popped into my head. It is ironic,
of course, because I know the answer now.

2965
04:33:42,311 --> 04:33:52,189
I know what it’s like to be day and night
now; always together, forever apart.

2966
04:33:52,189 --> 04:34:00,701
There is beauty where we sit this afternoon,
Allie and I. This is the pinnacle of my life.

2967
04:34:00,701 --> 04:34:07,219
They are here at the creek: the birds, the
geese, my friends. Their bodies float on the

2968
04:34:07,219 --> 04:34:11,969
cool water, which reflects bits and pieces
of their colors and make them seem larger

2969
04:34:11,969 --> 04:34:18,490
than they really are. Allie too is taken in
by their wonder, and little by little we get

2970
04:34:18,490 --> 04:34:21,109
to know each other again.

2971
04:34:21,109 --> 04:34:29,299
“It’s good to talk to you. I find that
I miss it, even when it hasn’t been that

2972
04:34:29,299 --> 04:34:30,969
long.”

2973
04:34:30,969 --> 04:34:36,320
I am sincere and she knows this, but she is
still wary. I am a stranger.

2974
04:34:36,320 --> 04:34:45,000
“Is this something we do often?” she asks.
“Do we sit here and watch the birds a lot?

2975
04:34:45,000 --> 04:34:49,211
I mean, do we know each other well?”

2976
04:34:49,211 --> 04:35:00,250
“Yes and no. I think everyone has secrets,
but we have been acquainted for years.”

2977
04:35:00,250 --> 04:35:06,760
She looks to her hands, then mine. She thinks
about this for a moment, her face at such

2978
04:35:06,760 --> 04:35:14,250
an angle that she looks young again. We do
not wear our rings. Again, there is a reason

2979
04:35:14,250 --> 04:35:17,070
for this. She asks:

2980
04:35:17,070 --> 04:35:20,000
“Were you ever married?”

2981
04:35:20,000 --> 04:35:22,020
I nod.

2982
04:35:22,020 --> 04:35:23,029
“Yes.”

2983
04:35:23,029 --> 04:35:24,510
“What was she like?”

2984
04:35:24,510 --> 04:35:27,189
I tell the truth.

2985
04:35:27,189 --> 04:35:34,561
“She was my dream. She made me who I am,
and holding her in my arms was more natural

2986
04:35:34,561 --> 04:35:39,840
to me than my own heartbeat. I think about
her all the time. Even now, when I’m sitting

2987
04:35:39,840 --> 04:35:45,859
here, I think about her. There could never
have been another.”

2988
04:35:45,859 --> 04:35:52,340
She takes this in. I don’t know how she
feels about this. Finally she speaks softly,

2989
04:35:52,340 --> 04:35:58,650
her voice angelic, sensual. I wonder if she
knows I think these things.

2990
04:35:58,650 --> 04:36:01,010
“Is she dead?”

2991
04:36:01,010 --> 04:36:10,180
What is death? I wonder, but I do not say
this. Instead I answer, “My wife is alive

2992
04:36:10,180 --> 04:36:14,010
in my heart. And she always will be.”

2993
04:36:14,010 --> 04:36:17,840
“You still love her, don’t you?”

2994
04:36:17,840 --> 04:36:24,520
“Of course. But I love many things. I love
to sit here with you. I love to share the

2995
04:36:24,520 --> 04:36:30,949
beauty of this place with someone I care about.
I love to watch the osprey swoop toward the

2996
04:36:30,949 --> 04:36:34,881
creek and find its dinner.”

2997
04:36:34,881 --> 04:36:40,090
She is quiet for a moment. She looks away
so I can’t see her face. It has been her

2998
04:36:40,090 --> 04:36:42,359
habit for years.

2999
04:36:42,359 --> 04:36:51,680
“Why are you doing this?” No fear, just
curiosity. This is good. I know what she means,

3000
04:36:51,680 --> 04:36:53,230
but I ask anyway.

3001
04:36:53,230 --> 04:36:54,230
“What?”

3002
04:36:54,230 --> 04:37:01,330
“Why are you spending the day with me?”
I smile.

3003
04:37:01,330 --> 04:37:08,632
“I’m here because this is where I’m
supposed to be. It’s not complicated. Both

3004
04:37:08,632 --> 04:37:15,510
you and I are enjoying ourselves. Don’t
dismiss my time with you—it’s not wasted.

3005
04:37:15,510 --> 04:37:23,080
It’s what I want. I sit here and we talk
and I think to myself, What could be better

3006
04:37:23,080 --> 04:37:27,129
than what I am doing now?”

3007
04:37:27,129 --> 04:37:34,400
She looks me in the eyes, and for a moment,
just a moment, her eyes twinkle. A slight

3008
04:37:34,400 --> 04:37:36,730
smile forms on her lips.

3009
04:37:36,730 --> 04:37:46,289
“I like being with you, but if getting me
intrigued is what you’re after, you’ve

3010
04:37:46,289 --> 04:37:53,831
succeeded. I admit I enjoy your company, but
I know nothing about you. I don’t expect

3011
04:37:53,831 --> 04:37:59,830
you to tell me your life story, but why are
you so mysterious?”

3012
04:37:59,830 --> 04:38:04,871
“I read once that women love mysterious
strangers.”

3013
04:38:04,871 --> 04:38:13,709
“See, you haven’t really answered the
question. You haven’t answered most of my

3014
04:38:13,709 --> 04:38:19,061
questions. You didn’t even tell me how the
story ended this morning.”

3015
04:38:19,061 --> 04:38:29,730
I shrug. We sit quietly for a while. Finally
I ask: “Is it true?”

3016
04:38:29,730 --> 04:38:31,631
“Is what true?”

3017
04:38:31,631 --> 04:38:36,330
“That women love mysterious strangers?”

3018
04:38:36,330 --> 04:38:41,480
She thinks about this and laughs. Then she
answers as I would:

3019
04:38:41,480 --> 04:38:44,590
“I think some women do.”

3020
04:38:44,590 --> 04:38:46,371
“Do you?”

3021
04:38:46,371 --> 04:38:54,609
“Now don’t go putting me on the spot.
I don’t know you well enough for that.”

3022
04:38:54,609 --> 04:38:59,430
She is teasing me, and I enjoy it.

3023
04:38:59,430 --> 04:39:05,859
We sit silently and watch the world around
us. This has taken us a lifetime to learn.

3024
04:39:05,859 --> 04:39:10,539
It seems only the old are able to sit next
to one another and not say anything and still

3025
04:39:10,539 --> 04:39:20,250
feel content. The young, brash and impatient,
must always break the silence. It is a waste,

3026
04:39:20,250 --> 04:39:27,920
for silence is pure. Silence is holy. It draws
people together because only those who are

3027
04:39:27,920 --> 04:39:34,439
comfortable with each other can sit without
speaking. This is the great paradox.

3028
04:39:34,439 --> 04:39:44,931
Time passes, and gradually our breathing begins
to coincide just as it did this morning. Deep

3029
04:39:44,931 --> 04:39:52,810
breaths, relaxed breaths, and there is a moment
when she dozes off, like those comfortable

3030
04:39:52,810 --> 04:40:00,730
with one another often do. I wonder if the
young are capable of enjoying this. Finally,

3031
04:40:00,730 --> 04:40:02,620
when she wakes, a miracle.

3032
04:40:02,620 --> 04:40:08,230
“Do you see that bird?” She points to
it, and I strain my eyes. It is a wonder I

3033
04:40:08,230 --> 04:40:14,330
can see it, but I can because the sun is bright.
I point, too.

3034
04:40:14,330 --> 04:40:21,638
“Caspian stern,” I say softly, and we
devote our attention to it and stare as it

3035
04:40:21,638 --> 04:40:29,180
glides over Brices Creek. And, like an old
habit rediscovered, when I lower my arm, I

3036
04:40:29,180 --> 04:40:37,200
put my hand on her knee and she doesn’t
make me move it.

3037
04:40:37,200 --> 04:40:44,138
She is right about my evasiveness. On days
like these, when only her memory is gone,

3038
04:40:44,138 --> 04:40:50,450
I am vague in my answers because I’ve hurt
my wife unintentionally with careless slips

3039
04:40:50,450 --> 04:40:58,330
of my tongue many times these past few years,
and I am determined not to let it happen again.

3040
04:40:58,330 --> 04:41:06,560
So I limit myself and answer only what is
asked, sometimes not too well, and I volunteer

3041
04:41:06,560 --> 04:41:08,862
nothing.

3042
04:41:08,862 --> 04:41:15,048
This is a split decision, both good and bad,
but necessary, for with knowledge comes pain.

3043
04:41:15,048 --> 04:41:21,708
To limit the pain I limit my answers. There
are days she never learns of her children

3044
04:41:21,708 --> 04:41:27,670
or that we are married. I am sorry for this,
but I will not change.

3045
04:41:27,670 --> 04:41:34,940
Does this make me dishonest? Perhaps, but
I have seen her crushed by the waterfall of

3046
04:41:34,940 --> 04:41:40,968
information that is her life. Could I look
myself in the mirror without red eyes and

3047
04:41:40,968 --> 04:41:48,540
quivering jaw and know I have forgotten all
that was important to me? I could not and

3048
04:41:48,540 --> 04:41:55,830
neither can she, for when this odyssey began,
this is how I began. Her life, her marriage,

3049
04:41:55,830 --> 04:42:03,128
her children. Her friends and her work. Questions
and answers in the game show format of This

3050
04:42:03,128 --> 04:42:05,080
Is Your Life.

3051
04:42:05,080 --> 04:42:11,660
The days were hard on both of us. I was an
encyclopedia, an object without feeling, of

3052
04:42:11,660 --> 04:42:18,270
the whos, whats and wheres in her life, when
in reality it is the whys, the things I did

3053
04:42:18,270 --> 04:42:23,990
not know and could not answer, that make it
all worthwhile. She would stare at pictures

3054
04:42:23,990 --> 04:42:30,030
of forgotten offspring, hold paintbrushes
that inspired nothing, and read love letters

3055
04:42:30,030 --> 04:42:37,150
that brought back no joy. She would weaken
over the hours, growing paler, becoming bitter,

3056
04:42:37,150 --> 04:42:44,160
and ending the day worse than when it began.
Our days were lost, and so was she. And selfishly,

3057
04:42:44,160 --> 04:42:47,160
so was I.

3058
04:42:47,160 --> 04:42:54,388
So I changed. I became Magellan or Columbus,
an explorer in the mysteries of the mind,

3059
04:42:54,388 --> 04:43:01,850
and I learned, bumbling and slow, but learning
nonetheless what had to be done. And I learned

3060
04:43:01,850 --> 04:43:09,080
what is obvious to a child. That life is simply
a collection of little lives, each lived one

3061
04:43:09,080 --> 04:43:16,298
day at a time. That each day should be spent
finding beauty in flowers and poetry and talking

3062
04:43:16,298 --> 04:43:23,080
to animals. That a day spent with dreaming
and sunsets and refreshing breezes cannot

3063
04:43:23,080 --> 04:43:32,900
be bettered. But most of all, I learned that
life is about sitting on benches next to ancient

3064
04:43:32,900 --> 04:43:42,510
creeks with my hand on her knee and sometimes,
on good days, for falling in love.

3065
04:43:42,510 --> 04:43:50,340
“What are you thinking?” she asks.

3066
04:43:50,340 --> 04:43:56,760
It is now dusk. We have left our bench and
are shuffling along lighted paths that wind

3067
04:43:56,760 --> 04:44:03,870
their way around this complex. She is holding
my arm, and I am her escort. It is her idea

3068
04:44:03,870 --> 04:44:10,040
to do this. Perhaps she is charmed by me.
Perhaps she wants to keep me from falling.

3069
04:44:10,040 --> 04:44:13,800
Either way, I am smiling to myself.

3070
04:44:13,800 --> 04:44:18,610
“I’m thinking about you.”

3071
04:44:18,610 --> 04:44:26,310
She makes no response to this except to squeeze
my arm, and I can tell she likes what I said.

3072
04:44:26,310 --> 04:44:34,560
Our life together has enabled me to see the
clues, even if she does not know them herself.

3073
04:44:34,560 --> 04:44:35,560
I go on:

3074
04:44:35,560 --> 04:44:40,030
“I know you can’t remember who you are,
but I can, and I find that when I look at

3075
04:44:40,030 --> 04:44:44,270
you, it makes me feel good.”

3076
04:44:44,270 --> 04:44:52,240
She taps my arm and smiles. “You’re a
kind man with a loving heart. I hope I enjoyed

3077
04:44:52,240 --> 04:44:57,128
you as much before as I do now.”

3078
04:44:57,128 --> 04:45:02,850
We walk some more. Finally she says, “I
have to tell you something.”

3079
04:45:02,850 --> 04:45:04,830
“Go ahead.”

3080
04:45:04,830 --> 04:45:10,760
“I think I have an admirer.”

3081
04:45:10,760 --> 04:45:12,740
“An admirer?”

3082
04:45:12,740 --> 04:45:13,740
“Yes.”

3083
04:45:13,740 --> 04:45:15,700
“I see.”

3084
04:45:15,700 --> 04:45:19,650
“You don’t believe me?”

3085
04:45:19,650 --> 04:45:22,620
“I believe you.”

3086
04:45:22,620 --> 04:45:24,600
“You should.”

3087
04:45:24,600 --> 04:45:25,600
“Why?”

3088
04:45:25,600 --> 04:45:31,638
“Because I think it is you.”

3089
04:45:31,638 --> 04:45:37,380
I think about this as we walk in silence,
holding each other, past the rooms, past the

3090
04:45:37,380 --> 04:45:45,490
courtyard. We come to the garden, mainly wildflowers,
and I stop her. I pick a bundle—red, pink,

3091
04:45:45,490 --> 04:45:51,750
yellow, violet. I give them to her, and she
brings them to her nose. She smells them with

3092
04:45:51,750 --> 04:45:58,500
eyes closed and she whispers, “They’re
beautiful.” We resume our walk, me in one

3093
04:45:58,500 --> 04:46:04,218
hand, the flowers in another. People watch
us, for we are a walking miracle, or so I

3094
04:46:04,218 --> 04:46:10,160
am told. It is true in a way, though most
times I do not feel lucky.

3095
04:46:10,160 --> 04:46:13,650
“You think it’s me?” I finally ask.

3096
04:46:13,650 --> 04:46:14,650
“Yes.”

3097
04:46:14,650 --> 04:46:15,650
“Why?”

3098
04:46:15,650 --> 04:46:22,670
“Because I have found what you have hidden.”
“What?”

3099
04:46:22,670 --> 04:46:32,230
“This,” she says, handing a small slip
of paper to me. “I found it under my pillow.”

3100
04:46:32,230 --> 04:46:34,968
I read it, and it says:

3101
04:46:34,968 --> 04:46:43,120
The body slows with mortal ache, yet my promise
remains true at the closing of our days,

3102
04:46:43,120 --> 04:46:49,100
A tender touch that ends with a kiss will
awaken love in joyous ways.

3103
04:46:49,100 --> 04:46:52,760
“Are there more?” I ask.

3104
04:46:52,760 --> 04:46:57,548
“I found this in the pocket of my coat.”

3105
04:46:57,548 --> 04:47:03,830
Our souls were one, if you must know and never
shall they be apart;

3106
04:47:03,830 --> 04:47:07,260
With splendid dawn, your face aglow

3107
04:47:07,260 --> 04:47:11,530
I reach for you and find my heart.

3108
04:47:11,530 --> 04:47:19,360
“I see,” and that is all I say.

3109
04:47:19,360 --> 04:47:25,980
We walk as the sun sinks lower in the sky.
In time, silver twilight is the only remainder

3110
04:47:25,980 --> 04:47:34,540
of the day, and still we talk of the poetry.
She is enthralled by the romance.

3111
04:47:34,540 --> 04:47:39,639
By the time we reach the doorway, I am tired.
She knows this, so she stops me with her hand

3112
04:47:39,639 --> 04:47:46,460
and makes me face her. I do and I realize
how hunched over I have become. She and I

3113
04:47:46,460 --> 04:47:53,350
are now level. Sometimes I am glad she doesn’t
know how much I have changed. She turns to

3114
04:47:53,350 --> 04:47:55,388
me and stares for a long time.

3115
04:47:55,388 --> 04:47:59,958
“What are you doing?” I ask.

3116
04:47:59,958 --> 04:48:06,740
“I don’t want to forget you or this day,
and I’m trying to keep your memory alive.”

3117
04:48:06,740 --> 04:48:17,620
Will it work this time? I wonder, then know
it will not. It can’t. I do not tell her

3118
04:48:17,620 --> 04:48:21,968
my thoughts, though. I smile instead because
her words are sweet.

3119
04:48:21,968 --> 04:48:23,840
“Thank you,” I say.

3120
04:48:23,840 --> 04:48:31,330
“I mean it. I don’t want to forget you
again. You’re very special to me. I don’t

3121
04:48:31,330 --> 04:48:35,500
know what I would have done without you today.”

3122
04:48:35,500 --> 04:48:41,910
My throat closes a little. There is emotion
behind her words, the emotions I feel whenever

3123
04:48:41,910 --> 04:48:50,110
I think of her. I know this is why I live,
and I love her dearly at this moment. How

3124
04:48:50,110 --> 04:48:55,138
I wish I were strong enough to carry her in
my arms to paradise.

3125
04:48:55,138 --> 04:49:01,700
“Don’t try to say anything,” she tells
me. “Let’s just feel the moment.”

3126
04:49:01,700 --> 04:49:10,800
And I do, and I feel heaven.

3127
04:49:10,800 --> 04:49:20,480
Her disease is worse now than it was in the
beginning, though Allie is different from

3128
04:49:20,480 --> 04:49:25,590
most. There are three others with the disease
here, and these three are the sum of my practical

3129
04:49:25,590 --> 04:49:31,770
experience with it. They, unlike Allie, are
in the most advanced stages of Alzheimer’s

3130
04:49:31,770 --> 04:49:37,958
and are almost completely lost. They wake
up hallucinating and confused. They repeat

3131
04:49:37,958 --> 04:49:44,630
themselves over and over. Two of the three
can’t feed themselves and will die soon.

3132
04:49:44,630 --> 04:49:51,548
The third has a tendency to wander and get
lost. She was found once in a stranger’s

3133
04:49:51,548 --> 04:49:59,550
car a quarter mile away. Since then she has
been strapped to the bed. All can be very

3134
04:49:59,550 --> 04:50:06,341
bitter at times, and at other times they can
be like lost children, sad and alone. Seldom

3135
04:50:06,341 --> 04:50:12,910
do they recognize the staff or people who
love them. It is a trying disease, and this

3136
04:50:12,910 --> 04:50:17,400
is why it is hard for their children and mine
to visit.

3137
04:50:17,400 --> 04:50:22,980
Allie, of course, has her own problems, too,
problems that will probably grow worse over

3138
04:50:22,980 --> 04:50:31,590
time. She is terribly afraid in the mornings
and cries inconsolably. She sees tiny people,

3139
04:50:31,590 --> 04:50:38,540
like gnomes, I think, watching her, and she
screams at them to get away. She bathes willingly

3140
04:50:38,540 --> 04:50:45,410
but will not eat regularly. She is thin now,
much too thin, in my opinion, and on good

3141
04:50:45,410 --> 04:50:48,190
days I do my best to fatten her up.

3142
04:50:48,190 --> 04:50:54,251
But this is where the similarity ends. This
is why Allie is considered a miracle, because

3143
04:50:54,251 --> 04:51:01,790
sometimes, just sometimes, after I read to
her, her condition isn’t so bad. There is

3144
04:51:01,790 --> 04:51:08,560
no explanation for this. “It’s impossible,”
the doctors say. “She must not have Alzheimer’s.”

3145
04:51:08,560 --> 04:51:16,628
But she does. On most days and every morning
there can be no doubt. On this there is agreement.

3146
04:51:16,628 --> 04:51:23,330
But why, then, is her condition different?
Why does she sometimes change after I read?

3147
04:51:23,330 --> 04:51:30,280
I tell the doctors the reason—I know it
in my heart, but I am not believed. Instead

3148
04:51:30,280 --> 04:51:36,940
they look to science. Four times specialists
have traveled from Chapel Hill to find the

3149
04:51:36,940 --> 04:51:44,112
answer. Four times they have left without
understanding. I tell them, “You can’t

3150
04:51:44,112 --> 04:51:49,670
possibly understand it if you use only your
training and your books,” but they shake

3151
04:51:49,670 --> 04:51:55,060
their heads and answer: “Alzheimer’s does
not work like this. With her condition, it’s

3152
04:51:55,060 --> 04:52:01,600
just not possible to have a conversation or
improve as the day goes on. Ever.”

3153
04:52:01,600 --> 04:52:08,120
But she does. Not every day, not most of the
time, and definitely less than she used to.

3154
04:52:08,120 --> 04:52:17,990
But sometimes. And all that is gone on these
days is her memory, as if she has amnesia.

3155
04:52:17,990 --> 04:52:23,958
But her emotions are normal, her thoughts
are normal. And these are the days that I

3156
04:52:23,958 --> 04:52:31,850
know I am doing right.

3157
04:52:31,850 --> 04:52:37,390
Dinner is waiting in her room when we return.
It has been arranged for us to eat here, as

3158
04:52:37,390 --> 04:52:43,830
it always is on days like these, and once
again I could ask for no more. The people

3159
04:52:43,830 --> 04:52:48,510
here take care of everything. They are good
to me, and I am thankful.

3160
04:52:48,510 --> 04:52:53,450
The lights are dimmed, the room is lit by
two candles on the table where we will sit,

3161
04:52:53,450 --> 04:52:59,872
and music is playing softly in the background.
The cups and plates are plastic, and the carafe

3162
04:52:59,872 --> 04:53:05,720
is filled with apple juice, but rules are
rules and she doesn’t seem to care. She

3163
04:53:05,720 --> 04:53:09,790
inhales slightly at the sight. Her eyes are
wide.

3164
04:53:09,790 --> 04:53:12,570
“Did you do this?”

3165
04:53:12,570 --> 04:53:15,890
I nod and she walks in the room.

3166
04:53:15,890 --> 04:53:18,782
“It looks beautiful.”

3167
04:53:18,782 --> 04:53:26,590
I offer my arm in escort and lead her to the
window. She doesn’t release it when we get

3168
04:53:26,590 --> 04:53:35,690
there. Her touch is nice, and we stand close
together on this crystal springtime evening.

3169
04:53:35,690 --> 04:53:43,450
The window is open slightly, and I feel a
breeze as it fans my cheek. The moon has risen,

3170
04:53:43,450 --> 04:53:47,780
and we watch for a long time as the evening
sky unfolds.

3171
04:53:47,780 --> 04:53:55,770
“I’ve never seen anything so beautiful,
I’m sure of it,” she says, and I agree

3172
04:53:55,770 --> 04:53:56,968
with her.

3173
04:53:56,968 --> 04:54:04,720
“I haven’t, either,” I say, but I am
looking at her. She knows what I mean, and

3174
04:54:04,720 --> 04:54:08,970
I see her smile. A moment later she whispers:

3175
04:54:08,970 --> 04:54:16,570
“I think I know who Allie went with at the
end of the story,” she says.

3176
04:54:16,570 --> 04:54:18,958
“You do?”

3177
04:54:18,958 --> 04:54:20,150
“Yes.”

3178
04:54:20,150 --> 04:54:21,340
“Who?”

3179
04:54:21,340 --> 04:54:25,000
“She went with Noah.”

3180
04:54:25,000 --> 04:54:27,620
“You’re sure?”

3181
04:54:27,620 --> 04:54:28,930
“Absolutely.”

3182
04:54:28,930 --> 04:54:42,510
I smile and nod. “Yes, she did,” I say
softly, and she smiles back. Her face is radiant.

3183
04:54:42,510 --> 04:54:50,900
I pull out her chair with some effort. She
sits and I sit opposite her. She offers her

3184
04:54:50,900 --> 04:54:57,140
hand across the table, and I take it in mine,
and I feel her thumb begin to move as it did

3185
04:54:57,140 --> 04:55:06,330
so many years ago. Without speaking, I stare
at her for a long time, living and reliving

3186
04:55:06,330 --> 04:55:14,430
the moments of my life, remembering it all
and making it real. I feel my throat begin

3187
04:55:14,430 --> 04:55:22,780
to tighten, and once again I realize how much
I love her. My voice is shaky when I finally

3188
04:55:22,780 --> 04:55:24,010
speak.

3189
04:55:24,010 --> 04:55:32,650
“You’re so beautiful,” I say. I can
see in her eyes that she knows how I feel

3190
04:55:32,650 --> 04:55:36,520
about her and what I really mean by my words.

3191
04:55:36,520 --> 04:55:42,220
She does not respond. Instead she lowers her
eyes and I wonder what she’s thinking. She

3192
04:55:42,220 --> 04:55:51,690
gives me no clues, and I gently squeeze her
hand. I wait. With all my dreams, I know her

3193
04:55:51,690 --> 04:55:54,550
heart, and I know I’m almost there.

3194
04:55:54,550 --> 04:55:59,420
And then, a miracle that proves me right.

3195
04:55:59,420 --> 04:56:06,160
As Glenn Miller plays softly in a candlelit
room, I watch as she gradually gives in to

3196
04:56:06,160 --> 04:56:13,260
the feelings inside her. I see a warm smile
begin to form on her lips, the kind that makes

3197
04:56:13,260 --> 04:56:21,378
it all worthwhile, and I watch as she raises
her hazy eyes to mine. She pulls my hand toward

3198
04:56:21,378 --> 04:56:22,740
her.

3199
04:56:22,740 --> 04:56:30,840
“You’re wonderful. . . .” she says softly,
trailing off, and at that moment she falls

3200
04:56:30,840 --> 04:56:39,220
in love with me, too; this I know, for I have
seen the signs a thousand times.

3201
04:56:39,220 --> 04:56:44,808
She says nothing else right away, she doesn’t
have to, and she gives me a look from another

3202
04:56:44,808 --> 04:56:53,010
lifetime that makes me whole again. I smile
back, with as much passion as I can muster,

3203
04:56:53,010 --> 04:56:59,510
and we stare at each other with the feelings
inside us rolling like ocean waves. I look

3204
04:56:59,510 --> 04:57:05,020
around the room, then up to the ceiling, then
back at Allie, and the way she’s looking

3205
04:57:05,020 --> 04:57:13,420
at me makes me warm. And suddenly I feel young
again. I’m no longer cold or aching, or

3206
04:57:13,420 --> 04:57:18,720
hunched over or deformed, or almost blind
with cataractal eyes.

3207
04:57:18,720 --> 04:57:26,208
I’m strong and proud, and the luckiest man
alive, and I keep on feeling that way for

3208
04:57:26,208 --> 04:57:30,150
a long time across the table.

3209
04:57:30,150 --> 04:57:35,830
By the time the candles have burned down a
third, I am ready to break the silence. I

3210
04:57:35,830 --> 04:57:41,600
say, “I love you deeply, and I hope you
know that.”

3211
04:57:41,600 --> 04:57:51,010
“Of course I do,” she says breathlessly.
“I’ve always loved you, Noah.”

3212
04:57:51,010 --> 04:58:02,170
Noah, I hear again. Noah. The word echoes
in my head. Noah . . . Noah. She knows, I

3213
04:58:02,170 --> 04:58:06,360
think to myself, she knows who I am. . . .

3214
04:58:06,360 --> 04:58:09,770
She knows. . . .

3215
04:58:09,770 --> 04:58:18,070
Such a tiny thing, this knowledge, but for
me it is a gift from God, and I feel our lifetime

3216
04:58:18,070 --> 04:58:24,320
together, holding her, loving her, and being
with her through the best years of my life.

3217
04:58:24,320 --> 04:58:33,390
She murmurs, “Noah . . . my sweet Noah . . .” And
I, who could not accept the doctor’s words,

3218
04:58:33,390 --> 04:58:40,170
have triumphed again, at least for a moment.
I give up the pretense of mystery, and I kiss

3219
04:58:40,170 --> 04:58:45,030
her hand and bring it to my cheek and whisper
in her ear. I say:

3220
04:58:45,030 --> 04:58:49,450
“You are the greatest thing that has ever
happened to me.”

3221
04:58:49,450 --> 04:58:57,558
“Oh . . . Noah,” she says with tears in
her eyes, “I love you, too.”

3222
04:58:57,558 --> 04:59:06,120
If only it would end like this, I would be
a happy man.

3223
04:59:06,120 --> 04:59:13,200
But it won’t. Of this I’m sure, for as
time slips by, I begin to see the signs of

3224
04:59:13,200 --> 04:59:15,090
concern in her face.

3225
04:59:15,090 --> 04:59:20,750
“What’s wrong?” I ask, and her answer
comes softly.

3226
04:59:20,750 --> 04:59:27,730
“I’m so afraid. I’m afraid of forgetting
you again. It isn’t fair ...I just can’t

3227
04:59:27,730 --> 04:59:30,520
bear to give this up.”

3228
04:59:30,520 --> 04:59:37,840
Her voice breaks as she finishes, but I don’t
know what to say. I know the evening is coming

3229
04:59:37,840 --> 04:59:46,298
to an end, and there is nothing I can do to
stop the inevitable. In this I am a failure.

3230
04:59:46,298 --> 04:59:48,860
I finally tell her:

3231
04:59:48,860 --> 04:59:56,610
“I’ll never leave you. What we have is
forever.” She knows this is all I can do,

3232
04:59:56,610 --> 05:00:02,340
for neither of us wants empty promises. But
I can tell by the way she is looking at me

3233
05:00:02,340 --> 05:00:06,840
that once again she wishes there were more.

3234
05:00:06,840 --> 05:00:13,058
The crickets serenade us, and we begin to
pick at our dinner. Neither one of us is hungry,

3235
05:00:13,058 --> 05:00:20,290
but I lead by example and she follows me.
She takes small bites and chews a long time,

3236
05:00:20,290 --> 05:00:25,208
but I am glad to see her eat. She has lost
too much weight in the past three months.

3237
05:00:25,208 --> 05:00:31,950
After dinner, I become afraid despite myself.
I know I should be joyous, for this reunion

3238
05:00:31,950 --> 05:00:38,340
is the proof that love can still be ours,
but I know the bell has tolled this evening.

3239
05:00:38,340 --> 05:00:46,878
The sun has long since set and the thief is
about to come, and there is nothing I can

3240
05:00:46,878 --> 05:00:54,350
do to stop it. So I stare at her and wait
and live a lifetime in these last remaining

3241
05:00:54,350 --> 05:00:56,360
moments.

3242
05:00:56,360 --> 05:00:58,360
Nothing.

3243
05:00:58,360 --> 05:01:02,290
The clock ticks.

3244
05:01:02,290 --> 05:01:03,860
Nothing.

3245
05:01:03,860 --> 05:01:11,330
I take her in my arms and we hold each other.
Nothing.

3246
05:01:11,330 --> 05:01:17,928
I feel her tremble and I whisper in her ear.
Nothing.

3247
05:01:17,928 --> 05:01:23,470
I tell her for the last time this evening
that I love her.

3248
05:01:23,470 --> 05:01:27,760
And the thief comes.

3249
05:01:27,760 --> 05:01:33,830
It always amazes me how quickly it happens.
Even now, after all this time. For as she

3250
05:01:33,830 --> 05:01:40,570
holds me, she begins to blink rapidly and
shake her head. Then, turning toward the corner

3251
05:01:40,570 --> 05:01:46,190
of the room, she stares for a long time, concern
etched on her face.

3252
05:01:46,190 --> 05:01:53,180
No! my mind screams. Not yet! Not now ...not
when we’re so close! Not tonight! Any night

3253
05:01:53,180 --> 05:01:59,340
but tonight. . . . Please! The words are inside
me. I can’t take it again! It isn’t fair

3254
05:01:59,340 --> 05:02:01,090
. . . it isn’t fair....

3255
05:02:01,090 --> 05:02:05,680
But once again, it is to no avail.

3256
05:02:05,680 --> 05:02:16,070
“Those people,” she finally says, pointing,
“are staring at me. Please make them stop.”

3257
05:02:16,070 --> 05:02:17,100
The gnomes.

3258
05:02:17,100 --> 05:02:25,820
A pit rises in my stomach, hard and full.
My breathing stops for a moment, then starts

3259
05:02:25,820 --> 05:02:33,010
again, this time shallower. My mouth goes
dry, and I feel my heart pounding. It is over,

3260
05:02:33,010 --> 05:02:41,830
I know, and I am right. The sundowning has
come. This, the evening confusion associated

3261
05:02:41,830 --> 05:02:47,870
with Alzheimer’s disease that affects my
wife, is the hardest part of all. For when

3262
05:02:47,870 --> 05:02:56,218
it comes, she is gone, and sometimes I wonder
whether she and I will ever love again.

3263
05:02:56,218 --> 05:03:02,500
“There’s no one there, Allie,” I say,
trying to fend off the inevitable. She doesn’t

3264
05:03:02,500 --> 05:03:03,500
believe me.

3265
05:03:03,500 --> 05:03:05,040
“They’re staring at me.”

3266
05:03:05,040 --> 05:03:07,980
“No,” I whisper while shaking my head.

3267
05:03:07,980 --> 05:03:10,040
“You can’t see them?”

3268
05:03:10,040 --> 05:03:13,890
“No,” I say, and she thinks for a moment.

3269
05:03:13,890 --> 05:03:19,100
“Well, they’re right there,” she says,
pushing me away, “and they’re staring

3270
05:03:19,100 --> 05:03:21,308
at me.”

3271
05:03:21,308 --> 05:03:28,298
With that, she begins to talk to herself,
and moments later, when I try to comfort her,

3272
05:03:28,298 --> 05:03:30,590
she flinches with wide eyes.

3273
05:03:30,590 --> 05:03:36,680
“Who are you?” she cries with panic in
her voice, her face becoming whiter. “What

3274
05:03:36,680 --> 05:03:42,510
are you doing here?” There is fear growing
inside her, and I hurt, for there is nothing

3275
05:03:42,510 --> 05:03:48,680
I can do. She moves farther from me, backing
away, her hands in a defensive position, and

3276
05:03:48,680 --> 05:03:52,058
then she says the most heartbreaking words
of all.

3277
05:03:52,058 --> 05:03:58,660
“Go away! Stay away from me!” she screams.
She is pushing the gnomes away from her, terrified,

3278
05:03:58,660 --> 05:04:01,638
now oblivious of my presence.

3279
05:04:01,638 --> 05:04:07,888
I stand and cross the room to her bed. I am
weak now, my legs ache, and there is a strange

3280
05:04:07,888 --> 05:04:13,430
pain in my side. I don’t know where it comes
from. It is a struggle to press the button

3281
05:04:13,430 --> 05:04:19,370
to call the nurses, for my fingers are throbbing
and seem frozen together, but I finally succeed.

3282
05:04:19,370 --> 05:04:27,070
They will be here soon now, I know, and I
wait for them. While I wait, I stare at my

3283
05:04:27,070 --> 05:04:28,170
wife.

3284
05:04:28,170 --> 05:04:29,270
Ten...

3285
05:04:29,270 --> 05:04:30,270
Twenty . . .

3286
05:04:30,270 --> 05:04:36,560
Thirty seconds pass, and I continue to stare,
my eyes missing nothing, remembering the moments

3287
05:04:36,560 --> 05:04:44,388
we just shared together. But in all that time
she does not look back, and I am haunted by

3288
05:04:44,388 --> 05:04:48,830
the visions of her struggling with unseen
enemies.

3289
05:04:48,830 --> 05:04:57,580
I sit by the bedside with an aching back and
start to cry as I pick up the notebook. Allie

3290
05:04:57,580 --> 05:05:03,950
does not notice. I understand, for her mind
is gone.

3291
05:05:03,950 --> 05:05:09,650
A couple of pages fall to the floor, and I
bend over to pick them up. I am tired now,

3292
05:05:09,650 --> 05:05:16,690
so I sit, alone and apart from my wife. And
when the nurses come in they see two people

3293
05:05:16,690 --> 05:05:24,700
they must comfort. A woman shaking in fear
from demons in her mind, and the old man who

3294
05:05:24,700 --> 05:05:37,170
loves her more deeply than life itself, crying
softly in the corner, his face in his hands.

3295
05:05:37,170 --> 05:05:43,050
I spend the rest of the evening alone in my
room. My door is partially open and I see

3296
05:05:43,050 --> 05:05:48,900
people walk by, some strangers, some friends,
and if I concentrate, I can hear them talking

3297
05:05:48,900 --> 05:05:56,870
about families, jobs, and visits to parks.
Ordinary conversations, nothing more, but

3298
05:05:56,870 --> 05:06:04,770
I find that I envy them and the ease of their
communication. Another deadly sin, I know,

3299
05:06:04,770 --> 05:06:08,388
but sometimes I can’t help it.

3300
05:06:08,388 --> 05:06:13,860
Dr. Barnwell is here, too, speaking with one
of the nurses, and I wonder who is ill enough

3301
05:06:13,860 --> 05:06:20,138
to warrant such a visit at this hour. He works
too much, I tell him. Spend the time with

3302
05:06:20,138 --> 05:06:25,950
your family, I say, they won’t be around
forever. But he doesn’t listen to me. He

3303
05:06:25,950 --> 05:06:30,850
cares for his patients, he says, and must
come here when called. He says he has no choice,

3304
05:06:30,850 --> 05:06:37,780
but this makes him a man torn by contradiction.
He wants to be a doctor completely devoted

3305
05:06:37,780 --> 05:06:45,120
to his patients and a man completely devoted
to his family. He cannot be both, for there

3306
05:06:45,120 --> 05:06:52,190
aren’t enough hours, but he has yet to learn
this. I wonder, as his voice fades into the

3307
05:06:52,190 --> 05:07:00,080
background, which he will choose or whether,
sadly, the choice will be made for him.

3308
05:07:00,080 --> 05:07:07,620
I sit by the window in an easy chair and I
think about today. It was happy and sad, wonderful

3309
05:07:07,620 --> 05:07:14,280
and heart-wrenching. My conflicting emotions
keep me silent for many hours. I did not read

3310
05:07:14,280 --> 05:07:22,320
to anyone this evening; I could not, for poetic
introspection would bring me to tears. In

3311
05:07:22,320 --> 05:07:29,230
time, the hallways become quiet except for
the footfalls of evening soldiers. At eleven

3312
05:07:29,230 --> 05:07:34,080
o’clock I hear the familiar sounds that
for some reason I expected. The footsteps

3313
05:07:34,080 --> 05:07:36,360
I know so well.

3314
05:07:36,360 --> 05:07:38,110
Dr. Barnwell peeks in.

3315
05:07:38,110 --> 05:07:43,280
“I noticed your light was on. Do you mind
if I come in?”

3316
05:07:43,280 --> 05:07:46,850
“No,” I say, shaking my head.

3317
05:07:46,850 --> 05:07:51,530
He comes in and looks around the room before
taking a seat a few feet from me.

3318
05:07:51,530 --> 05:07:58,770
“I hear,” he says, “you had a good day
with Allie.” He smiles. He is intrigued

3319
05:07:58,770 --> 05:08:06,180
by us and the relationship we have. I do not
know if his interest is entirely professional.

3320
05:08:06,180 --> 05:08:08,798
“I suppose so.”

3321
05:08:08,798 --> 05:08:17,340
He cocks his head at my answer and looks at
me. “You okay, Noah? You look a little down.”

3322
05:08:17,340 --> 05:08:21,280
“I’m fine. Just a little tired.”

3323
05:08:21,280 --> 05:08:24,070
“How was Allie today?”

3324
05:08:24,070 --> 05:08:33,650
“She was okay. We talked for almost four
hours.” “Four hours? Noah, that’s . . . incredible.”

3325
05:08:33,650 --> 05:08:40,293
I can only nod. He goes on, shaking his head.
“I’ve never seen anything like it, or

3326
05:08:40,293 --> 05:08:44,808
even heard about it. I guess that’s what
love is all about. You two were meant for

3327
05:08:44,808 --> 05:08:49,878
each other. She must love you very much. You
know that, don’t you?”

3328
05:08:49,878 --> 05:08:57,730
“I know,” I say, but I can’t say anything
more. “What’s really bothering you, Noah?

3329
05:08:57,730 --> 05:09:00,990
Did Allie say or do something that hurt your
feelings?”

3330
05:09:00,990 --> 05:09:08,690
“No. She was wonderful, actually. It’s
just that right now I feel . . . alone.”

3331
05:09:08,690 --> 05:09:10,388
“Alone?”

3332
05:09:10,388 --> 05:09:12,090
“Yes.”

3333
05:09:12,090 --> 05:09:15,490
“Nobody’s alone.”

3334
05:09:15,490 --> 05:09:23,910
“I’m alone,” I say as I look at my watch
and think of his family sleeping in a quiet

3335
05:09:23,910 --> 05:09:32,730
house, the place he should be, “and so are
you.”

3336
05:09:32,730 --> 05:09:39,920
The next few days passed without significance.
Allie was unable to recognize me at any time,

3337
05:09:39,920 --> 05:09:45,810
and I admit my attention waned now and then,
for most of my thoughts were of the day we

3338
05:09:45,810 --> 05:09:52,660
had just spent. Though the end always comes
too soon, there was nothing lost that day,

3339
05:09:52,660 --> 05:09:59,880
only gained, and I was happy to have received
this blessing once again.

3340
05:09:59,880 --> 05:10:04,260
By the following week, my life had pretty
much returned to normal. Or at least as normal

3341
05:10:04,260 --> 05:10:11,560
as my life can be. Reading to Allie, reading
to others, wandering the halls. Lying awake

3342
05:10:11,560 --> 05:10:17,950
at night and sitting by my heater in the morning.
I find a strange comfort in the predictability

3343
05:10:17,950 --> 05:10:19,310
of my life.

3344
05:10:19,310 --> 05:10:26,372
On a cool, foggy morning eight days after
she and I had spent our day together, I woke

3345
05:10:26,372 --> 05:10:32,170
early, as is my custom, and puttered around
my desk, alternately looking at photographs

3346
05:10:32,170 --> 05:10:39,361
and reading letters written many years before.
At least I tried to. I couldn’t concentrate

3347
05:10:39,361 --> 05:10:45,080
too well because I had a headache, so I put
them aside and went to sit in my chair by

3348
05:10:45,080 --> 05:10:51,800
the window to watch the sun come up. Allie
would be awake in a couple of hours, I knew,

3349
05:10:51,800 --> 05:10:58,650
and I wanted to be refreshed, for reading
all day would only make my head hurt more.

3350
05:10:58,650 --> 05:11:05,160
I closed my eyes for a few minutes while my
head alternately pounded and subsided. Then,

3351
05:11:05,160 --> 05:11:14,360
opening them, I watched my old friend, the
creek, roll by my window. Unlike Allie, I

3352
05:11:14,360 --> 05:11:19,969
had been given a room where I could see it,
and it has never failed to inspire me. It

3353
05:11:19,969 --> 05:11:26,770
is a contradiction—this creek—a hundred
thousand years old but renewed with each rainfall.

3354
05:11:26,770 --> 05:11:35,000
I talked to it that morning, whispered so
it could hear, “You are blessed, my friend,

3355
05:11:35,000 --> 05:11:44,940
and I am blessed, and together we meet the
coming days.” The ripples and waves circled

3356
05:11:44,940 --> 05:11:51,100
and twisted in agreement, the pale glow of
morning light reflecting the world we share.

3357
05:11:51,100 --> 05:12:02,280
The creek and I. Flowing, ebbing, receding.
It is life, I think, to watch the water. A

3358
05:12:02,280 --> 05:12:07,542
man can learn so many things.

3359
05:12:07,542 --> 05:12:13,931
It happened as I sat in the chair, just as
the sun first peeked over the horizon. My

3360
05:12:13,931 --> 05:12:22,470
hand, I noticed, started to tingle, something
it had never done before. I started to lift

3361
05:12:22,470 --> 05:12:27,820
it, but I was forced to stop when my head
pounded again, this time hard, almost as if

3362
05:12:27,820 --> 05:12:35,060
I had been hit in the head with a hammer.
I closed my eyes, then squeezed my lids tight.

3363
05:12:35,060 --> 05:12:41,140
My hand stopped tingling and began to go numb,
quickly, as if my nerves were suddenly severed

3364
05:12:41,140 --> 05:12:47,610
somewhere on my lower arm. My wrist locked
as a shooting pain rocked my head and seemed

3365
05:12:47,610 --> 05:12:54,400
to flow down my neck and into every cell of
my body, like a tidal wave, crushing and wasting

3366
05:12:54,400 --> 05:12:56,048
everything in its path.

3367
05:12:56,048 --> 05:13:03,770
I lost my sight, and I heard what sounded
like a train roaring inches from my head,

3368
05:13:03,770 --> 05:13:09,790
and I knew that I was having a stroke. The
pain coursed through my body like a lightning

3369
05:13:09,790 --> 05:13:16,410
bolt, and in my last remaining moments of
consciousness, I pictured Allie, lying in

3370
05:13:16,410 --> 05:13:22,080
her bed, waiting for the story I would never
read, lost and confused, completely and totally

3371
05:13:22,080 --> 05:13:25,500
unable to help herself. Just like me.

3372
05:13:25,500 --> 05:13:38,240
And as my eyes closed for the final time,
I thought to myself, Oh God, what have I done?

3373
05:13:38,240 --> 05:13:44,510
I was unconscious on and off for days, and
in those moments when I was awake, I found

3374
05:13:44,510 --> 05:13:50,960
myself hooked to machines, tubes up my nose
and down my throat and two bags of fluid hanging

3375
05:13:50,960 --> 05:13:57,770
near the bed. I could hear the faint hum of
machines, droning on and off, sometimes making

3376
05:13:57,770 --> 05:14:04,590
sounds I could not recognize. One machine,
beeping with my heart rate, was strangely

3377
05:14:04,590 --> 05:14:11,380
soothing, and I found myself lulled to never-land
time and time again.

3378
05:14:11,380 --> 05:14:16,160
The doctors were worried. I could see the
concern in their faces through squinted eyes

3379
05:14:16,160 --> 05:14:21,670
as they scanned the charts and adjusted the
machines. They whispered their thoughts, thinking

3380
05:14:21,670 --> 05:14:27,380
I couldn’t hear. “Strokes could be serious,”
they’d say, “especially for someone his

3381
05:14:27,380 --> 05:14:35,330
age, and the consequences could be severe.”
Grim faces would prelude their predictions—“loss

3382
05:14:35,330 --> 05:14:40,970
of speech, loss of movement, paralysis.”
Another chart notation, another beep of a

3383
05:14:40,970 --> 05:14:46,340
strange machine, and they’d leave, never
knowing I heard every word. I tried not to

3384
05:14:46,340 --> 05:14:50,968
think of these things afterward but instead
concentrated on Allie, bringing a picture

3385
05:14:50,968 --> 05:14:56,410
of her to my mind whenever I could. I did
my best to bring her life into mine, to make

3386
05:14:56,410 --> 05:15:04,540
us one again. I tried to feel her touch, hear
her voice, see her face, and when I did tears

3387
05:15:04,540 --> 05:15:10,090
would fill my eyes because I didn’t know
if I would be able to hold her again, to whisper

3388
05:15:10,090 --> 05:15:15,810
to her, to spend the day with her talking
and reading and walking. This was not how

3389
05:15:15,810 --> 05:15:22,440
I’d imagined, or hoped, it would end. I’d
always assumed I would go last. This wasn’t

3390
05:15:22,440 --> 05:15:25,470
how it was supposed to be.

3391
05:15:25,470 --> 05:15:30,000
I drifted in and out of consciousness for
days until another foggy morning when my promise

3392
05:15:30,000 --> 05:15:36,468
to Allie spurred my body once again. I opened
my eyes and saw a room full of flowers, and

3393
05:15:36,468 --> 05:15:42,160
their scent motivated me further. I looked
for the buzzer, struggled to press it, and

3394
05:15:42,160 --> 05:15:47,450
a nurse arrived thirty seconds later, followed
closely by Dr. Barnwell, who smiled almost

3395
05:15:47,450 --> 05:15:48,450
immediately.

3396
05:15:48,450 --> 05:15:54,360
“I’m thirsty,” I said with a raspy voice,
and Dr. Barnwell smiled broadly.

3397
05:15:54,360 --> 05:16:01,138
“Welcome back,” he said, “I knew you’d
make it.”

3398
05:16:01,138 --> 05:16:08,080
Two weeks later I am able to leave the hospital,
though I am only half a man now. If I were

3399
05:16:08,080 --> 05:16:12,400
a Cadillac, I would drive in circles, one
wheel turning, for the right side of my body

3400
05:16:12,400 --> 05:16:17,030
is weaker than the left. This, they tell me,
is good news, for the paralysis could have

3401
05:16:17,030 --> 05:16:23,190
been total. Sometimes, it seems, I am surrounded
by optimists.

3402
05:16:23,190 --> 05:16:29,718
The bad news is that my hands prevent me from
using either cane or wheelchair, so I must

3403
05:16:29,718 --> 05:16:36,420
now march to my own unique cadence to keep
upright. Not left-right-left as was common

3404
05:16:36,420 --> 05:16:43,380
in my youth, or even the shuffle-shuffle of
late, but rather slow-shuffle, slide-the-right,

3405
05:16:43,380 --> 05:16:51,750
slow-shuffle. I am an epic adventure now when
I travel the halls. It is slow going even

3406
05:16:51,750 --> 05:16:57,950
for me, this coming from a man who could barely
outpace a turtle two weeks ago.

3407
05:16:57,950 --> 05:17:04,491
It is late when I return, and when I reach
my room, I know I will not sleep. I breathe

3408
05:17:04,491 --> 05:17:10,380
deeply and smell the springtime fragrances
that filter through my room. The window has

3409
05:17:10,380 --> 05:17:16,580
been left open, and there is a slight chill
in the air. I find that I am invigorated by

3410
05:17:16,580 --> 05:17:22,790
the change in temperature. Evelyn, one of
the many nurses here who is one-third my age,

3411
05:17:22,790 --> 05:17:28,040
helps me to the chair that sits by the window
and begins to close it. I stop her, and though

3412
05:17:28,040 --> 05:17:34,920
her eyebrows rise, she accepts my decision.
I hear a drawer open, and a moment later a

3413
05:17:34,920 --> 05:17:42,570
sweater is draped over my shoulders. She adjusts
it as if I were a child, and when she is finished,

3414
05:17:42,570 --> 05:17:48,330
she puts her hand on my shoulder and pats
it gently. She says nothing as she does this,

3415
05:17:48,330 --> 05:17:56,140
and by her silence I know that she is staring
out the window. She does not move for a long

3416
05:17:56,140 --> 05:18:03,120
time, and I wonder what she is thinking, but
I do not ask. Eventually I hear her sigh.

3417
05:18:03,120 --> 05:18:08,958
She turns to leave, and as she does, she stops,
leans forward, and then kisses me on the cheek,

3418
05:18:08,958 --> 05:18:17,160
tenderly, the way my granddaughter does. I
am surprised by this, and she says quietly,

3419
05:18:17,160 --> 05:18:22,600
“It’s good to have you back. Allie’s
missed you and so have the rest of us. We

3420
05:18:22,600 --> 05:18:29,030
were all praying for you because it’s just
not the same around here when you’re gone.”

3421
05:18:29,030 --> 05:18:37,480
She smiles at me and touches my face before
she leaves. I say nothing. Later I hear her

3422
05:18:37,480 --> 05:18:43,638
walk by again, pushing a cart, talking to
another nurse, their voices hushed.

3423
05:18:43,638 --> 05:18:51,708
The stars are out tonight, and the world is
glowing an eerie blue. The crickets are singing,

3424
05:18:51,708 --> 05:18:58,510
and their sound drowns out everything else.
As I sit, I wonder if anyone outside can see

3425
05:18:58,510 --> 05:19:06,770
me, this prisoner of flesh. I search the trees,
the courtyard, the benches near the geese,

3426
05:19:06,770 --> 05:19:14,740
looking for signs of life, but there is nothing.
Even the creek is still. In the darkness it

3427
05:19:14,740 --> 05:19:21,628
looks like empty space, and I find that I’m
drawn to its mystery. I watch for hours, and

3428
05:19:21,628 --> 05:19:27,950
as I do, I see the reflection of clouds as
they begin to bounce off the water. A storm

3429
05:19:27,950 --> 05:19:35,980
is coming, and in time the sky will turn silver,
like dusk again.

3430
05:19:35,980 --> 05:19:43,128
Lightning cuts the wild sky, and I feel my
mind drift back. Who are we, Allie and I?

3431
05:19:43,128 --> 05:19:50,872
Are we ancient ivy on a cypress tree, tendrils
and branches intertwined so closely that we

3432
05:19:50,872 --> 05:19:58,942
would both die if we were forced apart? I
don’t know. Another bolt and the table beside

3433
05:19:58,942 --> 05:20:04,548
me is lit enough to see a picture of Allie,
the best one I have. I had it framed years

3434
05:20:04,548 --> 05:20:10,218
ago in the hope that the glass would make
it last forever. I reach for it and hold it

3435
05:20:10,218 --> 05:20:17,218
inches from my face. I stare at it for a long
time, I can’t help it. She was forty-one

3436
05:20:17,218 --> 05:20:22,820
when it was taken, and she had never been
more beautiful. There are so many things I

3437
05:20:22,820 --> 05:20:29,750
want to ask her, but I know the picture won’t
answer, so I put it aside.

3438
05:20:29,750 --> 05:20:38,400
Tonight, with Allie down the hall, I am alone.
I will always be alone. This I thought as

3439
05:20:38,400 --> 05:20:43,520
I lay in the hospital. This I’m sure of
as I look out the window and watch the storm

3440
05:20:43,520 --> 05:20:53,830
clouds appear. Despite myself I am saddened
by our plight, for I realize that the last

3441
05:20:53,830 --> 05:21:01,670
day we were together I never kissed her lips.
Perhaps I never will again. It is impossible

3442
05:21:01,670 --> 05:21:07,980
to tell with this disease. Why do I think
such things?

3443
05:21:07,980 --> 05:21:13,870
I finally stand and walk to my desk and turn
on the lamp. This takes more effort than I

3444
05:21:13,870 --> 05:21:19,058
think it will, and I am strained, so I do
not return to the window seat. I sit down

3445
05:21:19,058 --> 05:21:24,071
and spend a few minutes looking at the pictures
that sit on my desk. Family pictures, pictures

3446
05:21:24,071 --> 05:21:30,388
of children and vacations. Pictures of Allie
and me. I think back to the times we shared

3447
05:21:30,388 --> 05:21:36,650
together, alone or with family, and once again
I realize how ancient I am.

3448
05:21:36,650 --> 05:21:42,870
I open a drawer and find the flowers I’d
once given her long ago, old and faded and

3449
05:21:42,870 --> 05:21:49,458
tied together with ribbon. They, like me,
are dry and brittle and difficult to handle

3450
05:21:49,458 --> 05:21:55,790
without breaking. But she saved them. “I
don’t understand what you want with them,”

3451
05:21:55,790 --> 05:22:00,360
I would say, but she would just ignore me.
And sometimes in the evenings I would see

3452
05:22:00,360 --> 05:22:10,240
her holding them, almost reverently, as if
they offered the secret of life itself. Women.

3453
05:22:10,240 --> 05:22:16,468
Since this seems to be a night of memories,
I look for and find my wedding ring. It is

3454
05:22:16,468 --> 05:22:22,292
in the top drawer, wrapped in tissue. I cannot
wear it anymore because my knuckles are swollen

3455
05:22:22,292 --> 05:22:29,590
and my fingers lack for blood. I unwrap the
tissue and find it unchanged. It is powerful,

3456
05:22:29,590 --> 05:22:35,610
a symbol, a circle, and I know, I know, there
could never have been another. I knew it then,

3457
05:22:35,610 --> 05:22:42,888
and I know it now. And in that moment I whisper
aloud, “I am still yours, Allie, my queen,

3458
05:22:42,888 --> 05:22:50,480
my timeless beauty. You are, and always have
been, the best thing in my life.”

3459
05:22:50,480 --> 05:22:57,958
I wonder if she hears me when I say this,
and I wait for a sign. But there is nothing.

3460
05:22:57,958 --> 05:23:01,980
It is eleven-thirty and I look for the letter
she wrote me, the one I read when the mood

3461
05:23:01,980 --> 05:23:08,208
strikes me. I find it where I last left it.
I turn it over a couple of times before I

3462
05:23:08,208 --> 05:23:15,340
open it, and when I do my hands begin to tremble.
Finally I read:

3463
05:23:15,340 --> 05:23:19,310
Dear Noah,
I write this letter by candlelight as you

3464
05:23:19,310 --> 05:23:24,548
lie sleeping in the bedroom we have shared
since the day we were married. And though

3465
05:23:24,548 --> 05:23:31,888
I can’t hear the soft sounds of your slumber,
I know you are there, and soon I will be lying

3466
05:23:31,888 --> 05:23:38,070
next to you again as I always have. And I
will feel your warmth and your comfort, and

3467
05:23:38,070 --> 05:23:43,450
your breaths will slowly guide me to the place
where I dream of you and the wonderful man

3468
05:23:43,450 --> 05:23:48,702
you are.
I see the flame beside me and it reminds me

3469
05:23:48,702 --> 05:23:55,900
of another fire from decades ago, with me
in your soft clothes and you in your jeans.

3470
05:23:55,900 --> 05:24:01,760
I knew then we would always be together, even
though I wavered the following day. My heart

3471
05:24:01,760 --> 05:24:07,840
had been captured, roped by a southern poet,
and I knew inside that it had always been

3472
05:24:07,840 --> 05:24:15,020
yours. Who was I to question a love that rode
on shooting stars and roared like crashing

3473
05:24:15,020 --> 05:24:23,020
waves? For that is what it was between us
then and that is what it is today.

3474
05:24:23,020 --> 05:24:30,058
I remember coming back to you the next day,
the day my mother visited. I was so scared,

3475
05:24:30,058 --> 05:24:35,450
more scared than I had ever been because I
was sure you would never forgive me for leaving

3476
05:24:35,450 --> 05:24:41,452
you. I was shaking as I got out of the car,
but you took it all away with your smile and

3477
05:24:41,452 --> 05:24:47,820
the way you held your hand out to me. “How
’bout some coffee,” was all you said.

3478
05:24:47,820 --> 05:24:52,968
And you never brought it up again. In all
our years together.

3479
05:24:52,968 --> 05:24:58,131
Nor did you question me when I would leave
and walk alone the next few days. And when

3480
05:24:58,131 --> 05:25:03,058
I came in with tears in my eyes, you always
knew whether I needed you to hold me or to

3481
05:25:03,058 --> 05:25:11,450
just let me be. I don’t know how you knew,
but you did, and you made it easier for me.

3482
05:25:11,450 --> 05:25:17,730
Later when we went to the small chapel and
traded our rings and made our vows, I looked

3483
05:25:17,730 --> 05:25:23,490
in your eyes and knew I had made the right
decision. But more than that, I knew I was

3484
05:25:23,490 --> 05:25:28,000
foolish for ever
considering someone else. I have never wavered

3485
05:25:28,000 --> 05:25:33,360
since.
We had a wonderful life together, and I think

3486
05:25:33,360 --> 05:25:39,840
about it a lot now. I close my eyes sometimes
and see you with speckles of gray in your

3487
05:25:39,840 --> 05:25:44,702
hair, sitting on the porch and playing your
guitar while little ones play and clap to

3488
05:25:44,702 --> 05:25:50,770
the music you create. Your clothes are stained
from hours of work and you are tired, and

3489
05:25:50,770 --> 05:25:57,480
though I offer you time to relax, you smile
and say, “That’s what I am doing now.”

3490
05:25:57,480 --> 05:26:03,550
I find your love for our children very sensual
and exciting. “You’re a better father

3491
05:26:03,550 --> 05:26:09,601
than you know,” I tell you later, after
the children are sleeping. Soon after, we

3492
05:26:09,601 --> 05:26:16,388
peel off our clothes and kiss each other and
almost lose ourselves before we are able to

3493
05:26:16,388 --> 05:26:23,570
slip between the flannel sheets.
I love you for many things, especially your

3494
05:26:23,570 --> 05:26:29,501
passions, for they have always been those
things which are most beautiful in life. Love

3495
05:26:29,501 --> 05:26:37,530
and poetry and fatherhood and friendship and
beauty and nature. And I am glad you have

3496
05:26:37,530 --> 05:26:42,270
taught the children these things, for I know
their lives are better for it. They tell me

3497
05:26:42,270 --> 05:26:47,050
how special you are to them, and every time
they do, it makes me feel like the luckiest

3498
05:26:47,050 --> 05:26:52,370
woman alive.
You have taught me as well, and inspired me,

3499
05:26:52,370 --> 05:26:57,968
and supported me in my painting, and you will
never know how much it has meant to me. My

3500
05:26:57,968 --> 05:27:03,208
works hang in museums and private collections
now, and though there have been times when

3501
05:27:03,208 --> 05:27:09,230
I was frazzled and distracted because of shows
and critics, you were always there with kind

3502
05:27:09,230 --> 05:27:17,800
words, encouraging me. You understood my need
for my own studio, my own space, and saw beyond

3503
05:27:17,800 --> 05:27:24,600
the paint on my clothes and in my hair and
sometimes on the furniture. I know it was

3504
05:27:24,600 --> 05:27:32,110
not easy. It takes a man to do that, Noah,
to live with something like that. And you

3505
05:27:32,110 --> 05:27:38,140
have. For forty-five years now. Wonderful
years.

3506
05:27:38,140 --> 05:27:44,780
You are my best friend as well as my lover,
and I do not know which side of you I enjoy

3507
05:27:44,780 --> 05:27:52,388
the most. I treasure each side, just as I
have treasured our life together. You have

3508
05:27:52,388 --> 05:28:00,058
something inside you, Noah, something beautiful
and strong. Kindness, that’s what I see

3509
05:28:00,058 --> 05:28:07,820
when I look at you now, that’s what everyone
sees. Kindness. You are the most forgiving

3510
05:28:07,820 --> 05:28:15,440
and peaceful man I know. God is with you,
He must be, for you are the closest thing

3511
05:28:15,440 --> 05:28:21,750
to an angel that I’ve ever met.
I know you thought me crazy for making us

3512
05:28:21,750 --> 05:28:28,110
write our story before we finally leave our
home, but I have my reasons and I thank you

3513
05:28:28,110 --> 05:28:35,660
for your patience. And though you asked, I
never told you why, but now I think it is

3514
05:28:35,660 --> 05:28:41,128
time you knew.
We have lived a lifetime most couples never

3515
05:28:41,128 --> 05:28:48,080
know, and yet, when I look at you, I am frightened
by the knowledge that all this will be ending

3516
05:28:48,080 --> 05:28:58,280
soon. For we both know my prognosis and
what it will mean to us. I see your tears

3517
05:28:58,280 --> 05:29:03,570
and I worry more about you than I do about
me, because I fear the pain I know you will

3518
05:29:03,570 --> 05:29:10,970
go through. There are no words to express
my sorrow for this, and I am at a loss for

3519
05:29:10,970 --> 05:29:17,640
words.
So I love you so deeply, so incredibly much,

3520
05:29:17,640 --> 05:29:24,780
that I will find a way to come back to you
despite my disease, I promise you that. And

3521
05:29:24,780 --> 05:29:32,000
this is where the story comes in. When I am
lost and lonely, read this story—just as

3522
05:29:32,000 --> 05:29:39,570
you told it to the children—and know that
in some way, I will realize it’s about us.

3523
05:29:39,570 --> 05:29:44,830
And perhaps, just perhaps, we will find a
way to be together again.

3524
05:29:44,830 --> 05:29:51,548
Please don’t be angry with me on days I
do not remember you, and we both know they

3525
05:29:51,548 --> 05:29:58,760
